1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:01:36,665 --> 00:01:38,882
No. Cowboys and Indians. Bang-bang.

3
00:01:39,238 --> 00:01:41,283
Up the stairway all of you.
Go on. Hurry up. Quickly.

4
00:01:42,764 --> 00:01:44,036
Bang, bang, bang!

5
00:01:45,605 --> 00:01:48,100
Good job, Winifred. You got them
here right side up and kicking.

6
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,644
Kicking is right.
They are certainly a handful.

7
00:01:55,084 --> 00:01:56,909
I'm glad those kids are
here where it's safe.

8
00:01:57,339 --> 00:01:59,364
Make that "where it's safe as yet".

9
00:01:59,862 --> 00:02:02,674
Scare me some more. Tell me how it
is going to be when they bomb Omaha.

10
00:02:02,919 --> 00:02:04,428
It's not going to be nice, Junior.

11
00:02:04,616 --> 00:02:05,990
Not going to be nice at all.

12
00:02:08,183 --> 00:02:09,054
Six months.

13
00:02:10,038 --> 00:02:11,447
That's a long time to be away.

14
00:02:11,911 --> 00:02:13,096
Three years is longer.

15
00:02:13,826 --> 00:02:15,159
I'll sure be glad to see her.

16
00:02:15,711 --> 00:02:17,962
Who, the Statue of Liberty?
You've just passed her.

17
00:02:18,242 --> 00:02:20,238
Nope. I mean my other best girl.

18
00:02:22,115 --> 00:02:24,418
You say, your "other"?
- Sure. Her name is Paula.

19
00:02:24,893 --> 00:02:26,868
A great gal. I saw a
lot of her before I left.

20
00:02:28,408 --> 00:02:29,301
Paula, huh?

21
00:02:30,270 --> 00:02:31,599
You never told me about her.

22
00:02:31,870 --> 00:02:33,962
Do I have to tell you everything?
- Not a bad idea.

23
00:02:34,843 --> 00:02:36,864
Anybody I know?
- And nobody you owe either.

24
00:02:37,944 --> 00:02:39,216
I want to marry her, Jonny.

25
00:02:39,694 --> 00:02:40,550
No fooling?

26
00:02:40,723 --> 00:02:42,089
That's it exactly. No fooling.

27
00:02:43,006 --> 00:02:44,883
You think it is big,
important stuff, huh?

28
00:02:45,465 --> 00:02:46,966
And the babe? Likewise?

29
00:02:47,478 --> 00:02:49,044
From her letters, I'd say yes.

30
00:02:49,828 --> 00:02:51,432
It wasn't all set up before you left?

31
00:02:51,765 --> 00:02:54,983
Not quite. But this six months of
being apart has done it. Made it solid.

32
00:02:55,499 --> 00:02:56,364
Six months?

33
00:02:56,669 --> 00:02:58,999
If it took you that long to make
up your mind, it's no good.

34
00:02:59,538 --> 00:03:01,304
Nothing will come of it.
- How do you know?

35
00:03:03,174 --> 00:03:05,763
Nothing ever lasted six months with you.
Not even the seven-year itch.

36
00:03:06,027 --> 00:03:08,909
Maybe so, Junior. But when I
meet the ultimate babe, I'll know it.

37
00:03:09,444 --> 00:03:10,705
Like that! So will you.

38
00:03:11,231 --> 00:03:13,768
Well, I might be just
slow and sure, Jonny.

39
00:03:14,243 --> 00:03:15,880
Awful sure.
- Listen, Junior.

40
00:03:16,199 --> 00:03:18,346
Guys like us are strictly
cash and carry on.

41
00:03:18,790 --> 00:03:20,194
Make hay and then make tracks.

42
00:03:20,697 --> 00:03:22,897
A war correspondent has got
no business getting married.

43
00:03:24,016 --> 00:03:26,174
You're selling me, Jonny.
- And you're getting a bargain.

44
00:03:26,956 --> 00:03:29,419
It might have cost you a trip to
Reno to find out the same thing.

45
00:03:43,874 --> 00:03:45,344
Jonny, Kirk.
- Hi, honey.

46
00:03:46,555 --> 00:03:47,850
My goodness, Jonny.

47
00:03:48,335 --> 00:03:49,867
How is your goodness these days?

48
00:03:50,501 --> 00:03:52,678
You can tell our revered
editor we'll see him now.

49
00:03:53,077 --> 00:03:55,352
Jonny, Mr Stafford is pretty mad at you.

50
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:56,863
He's mad? Huh!

51
00:03:57,072 --> 00:04:00,140
In view of progress made in Washington
by the Japanese diplomatic mission.

52
00:04:01,044 --> 00:04:04,363
The prospect of war between this nation
and Japan becomes more remote that ever.

53
00:04:05,324 --> 00:04:07,651
As a matter of fact, informed
sources have indicated.

54
00:04:07,988 --> 00:04:10,063
That an unofficial agreement
to guarantee peace ..

55
00:04:10,485 --> 00:04:11,700
Has already been reached.

56
00:04:13,124 --> 00:04:15,470
Print that on page 1 column 8
for the banner line.

57
00:04:17,217 --> 00:04:18,062
Now, Davis.

58
00:04:18,390 --> 00:04:21,208
I must hear your version of why you and
your brother were kicked out of Germany.

59
00:04:21,602 --> 00:04:23,304
That's easy.
For tracking down the truth.

60
00:04:23,571 --> 00:04:24,500
And writing it.

61
00:04:24,921 --> 00:04:27,596
You're like all the crackpots who think
this country is headed for trouble.

62
00:04:28,029 --> 00:04:30,103
You're an old maid looking
under the bed for burglars.

63
00:04:30,940 --> 00:04:32,884
That's no place to look
for burglars nowadays.

64
00:04:33,309 --> 00:04:34,942
You'd find him right in bed with you.

65
00:04:35,197 --> 00:04:36,613
You disregarded my instructions.

66
00:04:37,112 --> 00:04:40,120
You kept on filing stories that offended
nations with which we are at peace.

67
00:04:40,604 --> 00:04:43,116
And you cut the heart and liver
out of our best despatches.

68
00:04:43,477 --> 00:04:45,508
We can't publish warmongering rumors.

69
00:04:45,844 --> 00:04:47,405
Alarmist tripe.
- "<i>Yes?</i>"

70
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:49,358
Send Charlie in.
I'm ready for my massage.

71
00:04:49,609 --> 00:04:51,185
You say tripe. I say truth.

72
00:04:51,994 --> 00:04:54,730
The only time a paper justifies its
existence is when it prints the truth.

73
00:04:54,830 --> 00:04:56,417
Not when it gets the most advertising.

74
00:04:57,129 --> 00:04:59,030
We've got a story that's
too hot for the cables.

75
00:04:59,130 --> 00:05:00,546
And we'll get it printed, Chief.

76
00:05:00,820 --> 00:05:02,579
The Chronicle isn't
the only paper in town.

77
00:05:02,914 --> 00:05:04,371
You can mail my pension to me.

78
00:05:05,090 --> 00:05:05,858
Hold on.

79
00:05:06,518 --> 00:05:08,449
Let me see this masterpiece.
- You won't like it.

80
00:05:08,846 --> 00:05:10,176
I paid for it. Let me see it.

81
00:05:21,110 --> 00:05:23,682
Well if ain't the Davis boys.
- Hiya, Charlie old boy.

82
00:05:23,782 --> 00:05:25,770
Greetings of the season, Charlie.
Long-time no rub.

83
00:05:25,881 --> 00:05:27,211
Hey, how did you find Berlin?

84
00:05:27,311 --> 00:05:28,756
Strictly by our sense of smell.

85
00:05:32,410 --> 00:05:33,339
Moral dynamite.

86
00:05:34,827 --> 00:05:36,672
Davis, I've got an ironclad
contract with you.

87
00:05:37,061 --> 00:05:39,449
You try to get this printed and
I'll run you out of the business.

88
00:05:39,852 --> 00:05:41,001
This story is dead.

89
00:05:43,514 --> 00:05:46,182
Here's the feature you'll read on the
front page of the Chronicle today.

90
00:05:47,146 --> 00:05:49,052
Safe, sane and solid.

91
00:05:52,705 --> 00:05:56,175
The news you feed the average man must
be as carefully chosen as his food.

92
00:05:56,700 --> 00:05:57,429
More so.

93
00:06:02,325 --> 00:06:04,445
It's a cinch he won't get
fat on what you hand out.

94
00:06:04,724 --> 00:06:05,968
I know my business, Davis.

95
00:06:06,282 --> 00:06:08,463
I know just how far
Mr John Q. Citizen will jump.

96
00:06:09,987 --> 00:06:11,164
All ready, Mr Stafford.

97
00:06:11,264 --> 00:06:12,391
Just a minute, Chief.

98
00:06:14,275 --> 00:06:15,977
Did you ever take a
good look at Charlie?

99
00:06:16,139 --> 00:06:16,725
No.

100
00:06:17,338 --> 00:06:18,939
What's wrong with him?
- Not a thing.

101
00:06:19,039 --> 00:06:20,551
He's Mr John Q. Citizen.

102
00:06:20,767 --> 00:06:22,016
You talk about him a lot.

103
00:06:22,373 --> 00:06:23,953
Take a good look at him.
- What for?

104
00:06:25,096 --> 00:06:27,470
Let's try that story out on him
and see how far he jumps.

105
00:06:27,806 --> 00:06:29,794
And if there is anything
wrong with where he lands.

106
00:06:30,876 --> 00:06:32,084
Alright, Davis.

107
00:06:32,623 --> 00:06:34,763
I don't mind giving you
a little object lesson.

108
00:06:35,608 --> 00:06:36,790
Charlie. Come here.

109
00:06:38,026 --> 00:06:39,842
Let's see what this does
to your horse sense.

110
00:06:42,346 --> 00:06:45,192
I'll give your side a real break.
You read it to him.

111
00:06:47,412 --> 00:06:48,141
Charlie.

112
00:06:49,264 --> 00:06:50,994
We're about to make
a one-man poll of you.

113
00:06:51,301 --> 00:06:52,545
You're a human guinea-pig.

114
00:06:52,795 --> 00:06:54,799
I'm taking bets right now
you will prove my point.

115
00:06:55,227 --> 00:06:57,307
So listen carefully
and be ready to jump.

116
00:07:00,338 --> 00:07:01,705
Just a minute, Chief.

117
00:07:04,432 --> 00:07:06,048
Gather round, Charlie. Right over here.

118
00:07:06,310 --> 00:07:07,311
You too, Junior.

119
00:07:11,846 --> 00:07:13,453
We want hear every word of this.

120
00:07:14,738 --> 00:07:15,643
Okay, Chief.

121
00:07:18,102 --> 00:07:21,530
"<i>By Jonny and Kirk Davis. Recently
returned correspondents in Berlin</i>."

122
00:07:21,934 --> 00:07:25,621
"<i>These facts gathered from the Japanese
embassy under curious circumstances</i>."

123
00:07:26,780 --> 00:07:27,995
Curious circumstances.

124
00:07:28,267 --> 00:07:30,186
I happen to know those
curious circumstances.

125
00:07:30,614 --> 00:07:33,994
Somebody gave the Japanese counsel
a Mickey Fin in a glass of Sake.

126
00:07:40,395 --> 00:07:42,555
"<i>The Pacific Ocean is not
nearly as wide as it seems</i> .."

127
00:07:42,655 --> 00:07:44,500
"<i>When you try to paddle
across it in a canoe</i>."

128
00:07:44,813 --> 00:07:46,513
"<i>At the Japanese general headquarters</i>."

129
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:48,920
"<i>Which has moved from
Tokyo to the Wilhelmstrasse</i>."

130
00:07:50,522 --> 00:07:52,630
You mean them two Aryans
is working together?

131
00:07:55,081 --> 00:07:57,811
"<i>Plans are being laid to stab the United
States of American in the back</i> .."

132
00:07:57,911 --> 00:07:59,756
"<i>While presumably patting
it on the shoulder</i>."

133
00:08:00,243 --> 00:08:02,715
"<i>No-one can foretell just
where the blow will fall</i>."

134
00:08:03,078 --> 00:08:05,351
"<i>But Japanese troop movements
and naval manoeuvres</i> .."

135
00:08:05,557 --> 00:08:07,689
"<i>While ostensibly aimed at
the subjection of China</i>."

136
00:08:08,224 --> 00:08:10,749
"<i>Are in reality, directed
at the United States</i>."

137
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:13,729
Now I leave it to you.

138
00:08:13,970 --> 00:08:16,020
Did you really expect me
to print a thing like that?

139
00:08:16,120 --> 00:08:17,315
Wouldn't that look fine?

140
00:08:18,066 --> 00:08:18,999
Where, boss?

141
00:08:19,108 --> 00:08:21,262
Where? You know where
you'd like to see it.

142
00:08:21,657 --> 00:08:24,887
You would like me to print it
page 1 column 8 with a banner line.

143
00:08:28,840 --> 00:08:30,848
Thanks. You gave it every break.

144
00:08:32,787 --> 00:08:33,692
Well, Charlie?

145
00:08:34,068 --> 00:08:36,886
What does the story you just heard make
you think the United states ought to do?

146
00:08:37,373 --> 00:08:39,132
I think the United States
ought to wise up.

147
00:08:39,232 --> 00:08:40,597
And go in there swinging.

148
00:08:42,198 --> 00:08:44,940
You see how you'll make Mister
Average Man react? He'd want to fight.

149
00:08:45,259 --> 00:08:47,501
What's wrong with that?
It's either fight or go under.

150
00:08:48,097 --> 00:08:50,020
There are ways of
avoiding a fight that ..

151
00:08:50,283 --> 00:08:52,500
Mr Average Man doesn't have
to worry his little head about.

152
00:08:52,663 --> 00:08:54,422
I'm a reporter, not a psychologist.

153
00:08:54,635 --> 00:08:56,528
Maybe there are ways
of avoiding a slugfest.

154
00:08:57,824 --> 00:08:59,612
Could it be that you are
getting some sense?

155
00:09:00,659 --> 00:09:01,502
It could be.

156
00:09:01,824 --> 00:09:02,639
I doubt it.

157
00:09:03,301 --> 00:09:04,453
Your kind never learn.

158
00:09:05,138 --> 00:09:06,296
You don't see straight.

159
00:09:06,584 --> 00:09:08,326
You are full of phony
ideas about people.

160
00:09:09,363 --> 00:09:10,465
People. Huh.

161
00:09:11,241 --> 00:09:13,780
Why can't you see the rank
and file as mostly rank.

162
00:09:15,635 --> 00:09:16,532
Say, boss.

163
00:09:17,494 --> 00:09:19,526
Isn't this record about due
in the composing room?

164
00:09:19,853 --> 00:09:21,690
It's overdue. Ring Miss Coulter.

165
00:09:22,125 --> 00:09:23,011
Okay boss.

166
00:09:23,496 --> 00:09:25,083
"<i>Yes, Mr Stafford?</i>"
- Come in, honey.

167
00:09:26,003 --> 00:09:26,989
Anything you say.

168
00:09:27,101 --> 00:09:28,431
I wish you meant that, Davis.

169
00:09:28,716 --> 00:09:30,961
You'd be the best man in your
field if you'd keep your head.

170
00:09:31,232 --> 00:09:32,218
I'm going to try.

171
00:09:32,575 --> 00:09:33,487
From now on.

172
00:09:35,176 --> 00:09:36,172
Yes, Mr Stafford?

173
00:09:36,587 --> 00:09:37,459
Miss Coulter.

174
00:09:37,958 --> 00:09:39,803
Get this moving. We're
holding up the edition.

175
00:09:44,071 --> 00:09:46,916
This is no time for butterfingers,
Honey. This is for posterity.

176
00:09:47,690 --> 00:09:50,430
I don't worry about being remembered.
I want people to know I'm here now.

177
00:09:50,656 --> 00:09:52,210
Oh, Expense account sheet.
- Yeah?

178
00:09:52,478 --> 00:09:53,821
I kept it down to the bone.

179
00:09:55,004 --> 00:09:55,756
Ah well.

180
00:10:04,375 --> 00:10:06,558
What's this? You bought
an observation balloon?

181
00:10:06,658 --> 00:10:08,531
It was an old one.
It belonged to the Persians.

182
00:10:11,839 --> 00:10:13,751
I think I'll go down and
say hello to the boys.

183
00:10:13,851 --> 00:10:16,146
Don't get in their way.
They've got an edition to print.

184
00:10:17,243 --> 00:10:18,305
[ Buzzer ]

185
00:10:19,083 --> 00:10:20,155
Answer it, will you.

186
00:10:24,243 --> 00:10:25,564
Office of the Grand Lama.

187
00:10:25,868 --> 00:10:27,470
"<i>What? Who is this?</i>"

188
00:10:28,563 --> 00:10:30,018
Jonny Davis. Remember?

189
00:10:31,492 --> 00:10:32,863
How are you, Pearcley?

190
00:10:33,514 --> 00:10:35,869
"<i>Tell the Chief I just ran his
record. What about that story?</i>"

191
00:10:37,392 --> 00:10:39,184
He wants to know
what about your feature.

192
00:10:40,218 --> 00:10:42,006
What does he mean:
"what about the feature"?

193
00:10:42,238 --> 00:10:42,996
Print it.

194
00:10:43,096 --> 00:10:44,025
The Chief says:

195
00:10:44,302 --> 00:10:46,374
What does he mean, what
about your feature. Print it.

196
00:10:46,720 --> 00:10:47,635
"<i>What's that?</i>"

197
00:10:47,983 --> 00:10:50,537
You tell Pearcley if he misses
the afternoon edition, he's fired.

198
00:10:52,044 --> 00:10:53,767
And if you miss the afternoon edition.

199
00:10:54,142 --> 00:10:55,043
You are fired.

200
00:10:55,462 --> 00:10:58,824
"<i>Well, alright. But this sure is a
switcheroo of The Chronicle policy</i>."

201
00:11:00,067 --> 00:11:01,224
"<i>The Chief never</i> .."

202
00:11:03,524 --> 00:11:04,576
What's this?

203
00:11:06,285 --> 00:11:07,300
What goes on here?

204
00:11:07,712 --> 00:11:08,841
What did Pearcley say?

205
00:11:11,337 --> 00:11:12,409
What record is this?

206
00:11:19,004 --> 00:11:19,979
Are you crazy?

207
00:11:20,666 --> 00:11:22,597
Listen Charlie, my story
is on that other record.

208
00:11:22,719 --> 00:11:23,620
Yeah?
- Yeah.

209
00:11:23,720 --> 00:11:25,593
It's the truth and it
belongs to guys like you.

210
00:11:25,714 --> 00:11:26,672
Are you with me?

211
00:11:26,907 --> 00:11:28,853
All the way. Ain't I one
of the rank and file?

212
00:11:29,358 --> 00:11:31,156
Come on, before that babe gets in here.

213
00:11:33,634 --> 00:11:34,836
Hello? Mr Stafford?

214
00:11:42,107 --> 00:11:43,438
Did Mr Stafford buzz me?

215
00:11:43,862 --> 00:11:45,477
No. He's getting the works, honey.

216
00:11:45,862 --> 00:11:46,478
Oh.

217
00:11:58,843 --> 00:12:00,856
Hey, if we keep this up
he will blow a gasket.

218
00:12:00,956 --> 00:12:03,113
He's too fat for wrestling,
- Five minutes to go.

219
00:12:03,213 --> 00:12:05,063
If we turn him loose
he'll run right and ..

220
00:12:05,163 --> 00:12:05,926
Charlie.

221
00:12:06,026 --> 00:12:07,487
I don't think he'll run very far.

222
00:12:07,845 --> 00:12:09,852
Not after the little object
lesson I will give him.

223
00:12:09,952 --> 00:12:10,624
Chief.

224
00:12:11,107 --> 00:12:12,179
You are an appeaser.

225
00:12:12,318 --> 00:12:13,983
And an appeaser always gets in the neck.

226
00:12:14,778 --> 00:12:18,289
He feels he gets what he wants by giving
away things he thinks he doesn't need.

227
00:12:19,219 --> 00:12:21,147
First .. he gives away his suit.

228
00:12:22,477 --> 00:12:23,578
That's the Rhineland.

229
00:12:24,753 --> 00:12:26,703
Then, he gives away his shoes.

230
00:12:27,372 --> 00:12:28,566
One is: Austria.

231
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:31,171
The other: Czechoslovakia.

232
00:12:31,922 --> 00:12:32,851
Then his socks.

233
00:12:33,398 --> 00:12:34,270
That's Spain.

234
00:12:34,872 --> 00:12:35,801
Then his shirt.

235
00:12:37,041 --> 00:12:38,008
That's Poland.

236
00:12:39,661 --> 00:12:41,590
And then his underpants. That's France.

237
00:12:42,302 --> 00:12:43,560
On the button, Charlie.

238
00:12:46,142 --> 00:12:48,544
Then there is only one thing
left for Mr Appeaser to do.

239
00:12:48,861 --> 00:12:50,628
Throw in the last thing he's got.

240
00:12:51,714 --> 00:12:52,783
The towel.

241
00:13:01,977 --> 00:13:03,499
You can let him up now, Charlie.

242
00:13:05,887 --> 00:13:06,781
Kirk.

243
00:13:07,577 --> 00:13:08,306
Clothes.

244
00:13:09,147 --> 00:13:09,926
Davis.

245
00:13:16,262 --> 00:13:17,906
He can still get somebody on that thing.

246
00:13:18,820 --> 00:13:19,664
Not anymore.

247
00:13:25,778 --> 00:13:27,041
This is sabotage.

248
00:13:30,357 --> 00:13:31,773
He is going to get Miss Coulter.

249
00:13:39,990 --> 00:13:42,113
I don't think he wants to
call a lady in here now.

250
00:13:42,611 --> 00:13:43,512
Do you, Chief?

251
00:13:48,214 --> 00:13:50,406
And that Charlie,
is how all appeasers end.

252
00:13:50,594 --> 00:13:52,276
Stripped of everything. Out in the cold.

253
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:54,844
Extra, extra! Read all about!

254
00:13:55,396 --> 00:13:56,875
Do I hear those presses roar?

255
00:13:59,414 --> 00:14:00,365
Hello, Chief.

256
00:14:00,465 --> 00:14:01,171
I do.

257
00:14:02,117 --> 00:14:03,664
Here you are, Jonny. Page 1.

258
00:14:04,427 --> 00:14:05,379
Good work, kid.

259
00:14:05,479 --> 00:14:07,595
"<i>Japan plots in Pacific</i>."
Well, what do you know?

260
00:14:07,695 --> 00:14:09,501
This is what the Chief
needs to stay warm.

261
00:14:09,601 --> 00:14:11,403
Here you are, sire.
Someday you'll thank me.

262
00:14:11,619 --> 00:14:12,624
Come on, Charlie.

263
00:14:13,150 --> 00:14:13,987
My hat.

264
00:14:14,830 --> 00:14:16,677
Beat it down to the cashier
with our expenses.

265
00:14:16,777 --> 00:14:17,971
No. My girl's waiting.

266
00:14:18,071 --> 00:14:19,788
She'll wait for an hour. She's spoilt.

267
00:14:19,888 --> 00:14:21,631
But I'm late now.
- Go on. Get going.

268
00:14:21,999 --> 00:14:23,958
I'll meet you at Evie Manning's.
Pick up our bags.

269
00:14:24,797 --> 00:14:26,738
Mr Stafford wants you right away.

270
00:14:26,982 --> 00:14:28,598
He's not buzzing me.
- Oh, he will be.

271
00:14:28,698 --> 00:14:30,104
He'll be buzzing everybody.

272
00:14:30,204 --> 00:14:31,190
Come on, Charlie.

273
00:14:35,513 --> 00:14:37,221
They'll never work on another newspaper.

274
00:14:37,412 --> 00:14:38,513
I'll bash that Davis.

275
00:14:40,382 --> 00:14:42,904
Do something! Get me a pair of pants!

276
00:14:47,941 --> 00:14:48,923
Willy.
- Uhuh?

277
00:14:49,269 --> 00:14:50,255
How do they look?

278
00:14:50,440 --> 00:14:51,401
They'll be fine.

279
00:14:51,763 --> 00:14:53,240
Sure, after they leave your easel.

280
00:14:53,340 --> 00:14:56,652
Don't run down your legs, honey.
They've supported both of us for years.

281
00:14:56,899 --> 00:14:57,657
Too long.

282
00:14:57,823 --> 00:15:00,804
Some women only worry about double
chins. I stew about my knees falling.

283
00:15:01,157 --> 00:15:02,458
Anybody here?
- It's Jonny.

284
00:15:02,749 --> 00:15:03,605
Nobody else.

285
00:15:05,978 --> 00:15:07,402
I'm back.
- Darling!

286
00:15:11,374 --> 00:15:12,792
Why didn't you warn us?

287
00:15:12,892 --> 00:15:14,021
Yeah. We'd have moved.

288
00:15:14,691 --> 00:15:17,109
What's new in the world?
- My by-line is inside.

289
00:15:17,386 --> 00:15:20,254
For further information see today's
Chronicle. The Davis edition.

290
00:15:20,439 --> 00:15:21,340
Where is Kirk?

291
00:15:21,633 --> 00:15:22,733
He'll be around.

292
00:15:26,320 --> 00:15:27,335
Home on the range.

293
00:15:29,316 --> 00:15:30,758
Well. What's with you?

294
00:15:30,976 --> 00:15:32,834
Still selling stockings
with Evie's legs.

295
00:15:33,092 --> 00:15:34,711
You know, it's like I told you, Willie.

296
00:15:34,811 --> 00:15:36,889
There's no dough in legs.
You should do a comic strip.

297
00:15:36,989 --> 00:15:38,605
A comic strip? What do you call these?

298
00:15:42,134 --> 00:15:43,349
Hey, where is my ashtray?

299
00:15:44,166 --> 00:15:44,809
Here.

300
00:15:45,311 --> 00:15:46,269
You've moved it.

301
00:15:46,678 --> 00:15:48,598
Listen, my lamb.
You've been gone three years.

302
00:15:48,846 --> 00:15:50,178
I dusted a couple of times.

303
00:15:50,839 --> 00:15:51,968
When, the first month?

304
00:15:52,962 --> 00:15:55,965
Why not stop being a bully on the block?
- You got clean sheets on my bed?

305
00:15:56,403 --> 00:15:57,345
Yes and no.

306
00:15:57,683 --> 00:15:59,739
What you mean, yes and no?
You sound like a diplomat.

307
00:15:59,839 --> 00:16:02,047
That's what I'm trying to be.
I rented the room.

308
00:16:02,382 --> 00:16:03,693
What?
- After all, Jonny.

309
00:16:03,864 --> 00:16:05,928
He'll find his trunk in the
hall when he gets back.

310
00:16:06,028 --> 00:16:07,704
It's a girl and she likes to be alone.

311
00:16:07,975 --> 00:16:09,086
In isolation, huh?

312
00:16:09,319 --> 00:16:10,545
You can't go up there.

313
00:16:11,764 --> 00:16:12,350
Ow!

314
00:16:12,805 --> 00:16:13,549
Ow!

315
00:16:15,103 --> 00:16:17,150
Will you kindly get this
so-and-so out of my room.

316
00:16:17,728 --> 00:16:18,624
Your room?

317
00:16:18,852 --> 00:16:21,141
Hey, I bought that very bathtub
you're putting rings on.

318
00:16:21,453 --> 00:16:22,380
Are you going?

319
00:16:22,880 --> 00:16:24,038
Not without a struggle.

320
00:16:24,792 --> 00:16:27,103
Then will you please hand me my robe?

321
00:16:27,517 --> 00:16:29,291
So I can throw you out, Mr Davis.

322
00:16:30,280 --> 00:16:31,797
May I have your name in full?

323
00:16:32,162 --> 00:16:32,927
What for?

324
00:16:33,205 --> 00:16:35,210
Just call me "babe". You will anyway.

325
00:16:35,988 --> 00:16:37,378
This is a war of nerves.

326
00:16:37,873 --> 00:16:39,112
Shall I calm for them?

327
00:16:39,315 --> 00:16:40,673
The nerve is yours, my friend.

328
00:16:44,249 --> 00:16:46,436
Oh, can't ewe be more than just friends?

329
00:16:46,984 --> 00:16:48,024
But we are.

330
00:16:50,576 --> 00:16:52,166
But you still don't trust me.

331
00:16:53,065 --> 00:16:54,091
Now I do.

332
00:16:56,364 --> 00:16:58,875
Don't hurry. Most accidents
occur in the bathroom.

333
00:17:03,417 --> 00:17:05,655
Hey, you seem to think you know
a lot about me, don't you.

334
00:17:05,865 --> 00:17:08,199
Enough. If I put it in
writing you could sue me.

335
00:17:08,809 --> 00:17:09,452
Yeah?

336
00:17:10,649 --> 00:17:13,333
Are you good to look at?
- Wouldn't it be more fun to guess?

337
00:17:13,858 --> 00:17:14,501
Okay.

338
00:17:14,952 --> 00:17:17,952
I'll reconstruct the missing body
from the evidence at hand.

339
00:17:18,805 --> 00:17:20,389
Now to begin with, the ..

340
00:17:21,666 --> 00:17:23,428
The body is quite a body.

341
00:17:23,690 --> 00:17:24,762
You're getting warm.

342
00:17:25,094 --> 00:17:26,743
You can raise that a couple of degrees.

343
00:17:28,597 --> 00:17:30,935
And you are under twenty-five
and terrific in the face.

344
00:17:31,403 --> 00:17:32,876
You'd have to be to wear this hat.

345
00:17:34,492 --> 00:17:36,572
Now let's see. Color of hair.

346
00:17:39,095 --> 00:17:40,177
Yes, sir.

347
00:17:40,594 --> 00:17:42,132
Why, you are a beautiful blond.

348
00:17:42,365 --> 00:17:43,973
Hey, get away from that keyhole!

349
00:17:44,610 --> 00:17:46,161
Yes, sir. A beautiful blond.

350
00:17:46,882 --> 00:17:47,883
Blue eyes.

351
00:17:48,346 --> 00:17:49,301
White skin.

352
00:17:49,545 --> 00:17:50,818
A good set of biting teeth.

353
00:17:51,014 --> 00:17:53,631
If you're not at the keyhole, how come
you know exactly what I look like?

354
00:17:53,905 --> 00:17:55,092
Wishful thinking, honey.

355
00:17:56,840 --> 00:17:59,226
Hey, you like yourself
a little bit, don't you.

356
00:17:59,592 --> 00:18:01,779
Well, there is a mirror
in here. Remember?

357
00:18:02,003 --> 00:18:03,123
Listen, Narcissus.

358
00:18:03,460 --> 00:18:07,126
These same clues could add up to
a frowzy, bleached, lantern-jawed ..

359
00:18:07,327 --> 00:18:09,873
Gimlet-eyed, leathery skinned,
knock-kneed old crone ..

360
00:18:09,973 --> 00:18:11,487
With a mistaken daring in hats.

361
00:18:11,885 --> 00:18:12,614
And a ..

362
00:18:15,137 --> 00:18:16,295
They do not, my friend.

363
00:18:17,270 --> 00:18:17,999
Do they?

364
00:18:24,808 --> 00:18:25,884
They do not.

365
00:18:28,820 --> 00:18:30,713
Of course we know each other.

366
00:18:31,448 --> 00:18:32,177
You bet.

367
00:18:32,387 --> 00:18:34,547
I'm sure glad to set eyes on you again.

368
00:18:34,853 --> 00:18:36,612
You know darned well
you don't remember me.

369
00:18:36,752 --> 00:18:37,428
What?

370
00:18:38,648 --> 00:18:39,949
How could I ever forget you?

371
00:18:42,034 --> 00:18:42,820
You won't.

372
00:18:43,937 --> 00:18:44,613
Again.

373
00:18:52,893 --> 00:18:53,907
How is Kirk?

374
00:18:54,647 --> 00:18:56,156
Oh, you know Kirk too, huh?

375
00:18:56,479 --> 00:18:59,325
Sure, I was the cub reporter when you
brought Kirk to the Chronicle office.

376
00:18:59,674 --> 00:19:01,090
Just before you left for Europe.

377
00:19:02,047 --> 00:19:05,056
Ah, yeah now I remember.
You were that blond girl.

378
00:19:05,837 --> 00:19:07,421
My hair was red at the time.

379
00:19:09,453 --> 00:19:11,040
Is Kirk still running errands for you?

380
00:19:11,511 --> 00:19:12,160
Why?

381
00:19:12,697 --> 00:19:15,611
Because one of the errands was to send
Kirk with a note asking me for a date.

382
00:19:17,150 --> 00:19:18,776
Oh, sure. Sure.

383
00:19:19,084 --> 00:19:20,357
Say, what a night that was.

384
00:19:20,575 --> 00:19:22,145
And what a conga you throw.

385
00:19:22,825 --> 00:19:24,098
It was the rumba that year.

386
00:19:24,560 --> 00:19:25,832
Anyway, we didn't dance.

387
00:19:26,101 --> 00:19:27,062
No?
- No.

388
00:19:27,468 --> 00:19:29,262
Well, how could I with a sprained ankle?

389
00:19:29,664 --> 00:19:31,891
But that was a swell
5-dollar dinner I blew you to.

390
00:19:32,202 --> 00:19:33,389
Not even a ham sandwich.

391
00:19:33,784 --> 00:19:34,767
No?
- No.

392
00:19:35,894 --> 00:19:38,120
Ah, now I remember.
I was on a liquid diet.

393
00:19:45,805 --> 00:19:46,706
Not your type.

394
00:19:47,555 --> 00:19:49,811
You ever tried Sweet Surrender?

395
00:19:51,103 --> 00:19:51,918
Not lately.

396
00:19:53,145 --> 00:19:55,668
We didn't dance, we didn't
drink, we didn't eat.

397
00:19:56,051 --> 00:19:57,444
We must have done something.

398
00:19:57,718 --> 00:19:59,388
Or were we just mental?

399
00:20:00,016 --> 00:20:01,031
It was all mental.

400
00:20:01,848 --> 00:20:03,482
Because you never kept the date.

401
00:20:05,160 --> 00:20:07,219
That's an oversight that
should be corrected.

402
00:20:08,692 --> 00:20:09,650
Some other year.

403
00:20:10,231 --> 00:20:11,074
Out, mister.

404
00:20:32,166 --> 00:20:33,582
You ought to have that patented.

405
00:20:34,719 --> 00:20:35,454
I will.

406
00:20:35,850 --> 00:20:37,380
After I work out a few improvements.

407
00:20:38,764 --> 00:20:40,057
I could suggest a couple.

408
00:20:40,957 --> 00:20:42,527
I'll learn faster if you show me.

409
00:20:43,901 --> 00:20:46,480
Hey you two. There is somebody
down here to see you.

410
00:20:47,496 --> 00:20:48,895
I think we're being paged.

411
00:20:49,471 --> 00:20:50,613
I don't hear a thing.

412
00:20:52,069 --> 00:20:52,865
I do.

413
00:20:59,432 --> 00:21:01,470
Well, thanks for the fraternity pin.

414
00:21:05,752 --> 00:21:06,706
Kirk, darling.

415
00:21:07,497 --> 00:21:08,582
You look wonderful.

416
00:21:08,816 --> 00:21:11,409
And you look good enough to eat,
which isn't such a bad idea.

417
00:21:23,601 --> 00:21:25,590
Evie, why didn't you
tell me it was Kirk?

418
00:21:25,800 --> 00:21:27,361
Well, seeing is believing, honey.

419
00:21:27,580 --> 00:21:29,568
Come on, Eve. We've got
to finish this stocking Ad.

420
00:21:30,208 --> 00:21:32,348
Here I am. Back on my pedestal.

421
00:21:32,786 --> 00:21:33,572
Hi, Jonny.

422
00:21:34,122 --> 00:21:35,423
I see you met Paula already.

423
00:21:36,533 --> 00:21:37,239
Yeah.

424
00:21:37,584 --> 00:21:38,799
Is she everything I said?

425
00:21:39,386 --> 00:21:40,197
And more.

426
00:21:41,413 --> 00:21:42,693
You have a good trip, Kirk?

427
00:21:42,793 --> 00:21:44,552
The only good part was
getting back, honey.

428
00:21:44,762 --> 00:21:46,530
Wait until you two
really get acquainted.

429
00:21:46,630 --> 00:21:47,817
Yeah, I can hardly wait.

430
00:21:48,183 --> 00:21:49,715
I'd really like to know her better.

431
00:21:51,825 --> 00:21:53,269
Well, to know her is to love her.

432
00:21:54,557 --> 00:21:56,185
I wouldn't be a bit surprised.

433
00:21:58,214 --> 00:22:00,107
Eve, weren't you amazed to see Kirk?

434
00:22:00,663 --> 00:22:01,443
I was.

435
00:22:01,721 --> 00:22:03,561
Nothing the Davis brothers
ever do fazes me.

436
00:22:03,772 --> 00:22:06,842
Do you mind if we use your couch, Jonny?
- No. Not if you don't bounce.

437
00:22:07,398 --> 00:22:09,128
Those springs aren't
what they used to be.

438
00:22:10,177 --> 00:22:12,854
Hey, we got to get ourselves a place
to roost. We can't move in on Paula.

439
00:22:13,307 --> 00:22:13,893
No?

440
00:22:15,117 --> 00:22:16,132
What do you think?

441
00:22:16,529 --> 00:22:17,201
Paula.

442
00:22:18,609 --> 00:22:19,826
Well, three is a crowd.

443
00:22:20,554 --> 00:22:22,534
We'll see about making that two, honey.

444
00:22:23,497 --> 00:22:25,551
I'll get our stuff over to the
Great Northern. Okay?

445
00:22:25,780 --> 00:22:27,633
I wouldn't think of
crossing you, Junior.

446
00:22:29,032 --> 00:22:30,018
How about dinner?

447
00:22:31,983 --> 00:22:33,403
Shall we all go out some place?

448
00:22:34,551 --> 00:22:35,652
I got to finish this.

449
00:22:36,988 --> 00:22:38,377
And he can't do it without me.

450
00:22:38,685 --> 00:22:40,450
Me, I've got a story to cover.

451
00:22:40,750 --> 00:22:41,440
Huh?

452
00:22:43,994 --> 00:22:45,278
I'll meet you here at nine.

453
00:22:46,020 --> 00:22:46,773
Okay.

454
00:22:48,226 --> 00:22:50,602
Well, I want to get into
something comfortable.

455
00:22:53,535 --> 00:22:54,550
See you all later.

456
00:22:56,832 --> 00:22:58,076
Well, how do you like her?

457
00:22:58,664 --> 00:22:59,792
So far, so good.

458
00:23:00,260 --> 00:23:02,828
Why didn't you tell me she lived here?
- You didn't give me a chance.

459
00:23:03,534 --> 00:23:05,722
You know, you really sold me
a bill of goods today, Jonny.

460
00:23:06,192 --> 00:23:08,516
The newspaper business
and matrimony don't mix.

461
00:23:09,214 --> 00:23:11,116
Well, I hope the lady won't
be too disappointed.

462
00:23:11,715 --> 00:23:13,495
It's the newspaper
business I'm giving up.

463
00:23:14,974 --> 00:23:16,968
I'll let you be flower girl
if Paula doesn't mind.

464
00:23:17,369 --> 00:23:18,890
Hey, do I hear wedding bells?

465
00:23:19,089 --> 00:23:20,463
Yeah. What goes on?

466
00:23:21,462 --> 00:23:23,335
Ah, she's the greatest
girl I ever knew, Jonny.

467
00:23:23,489 --> 00:23:26,045
Honest. Loyal. Straight from
the shoulder. You'll find out.

468
00:23:27,131 --> 00:23:28,302
Maybe I have already.

469
00:23:29,519 --> 00:23:31,694
Listen, Junior.
You're a war correspondent.

470
00:23:31,904 --> 00:23:33,491
And there is a war going on. Remember?

471
00:23:33,721 --> 00:23:35,628
You just can't walk out on it.
- I can.

472
00:23:35,936 --> 00:23:37,506
I got me a steady job all lined up.

473
00:23:37,829 --> 00:23:38,472
Yeah?

474
00:23:39,286 --> 00:23:41,544
Oh, listen, Jonny.
Everybody is not like you.

475
00:23:41,880 --> 00:23:43,496
You'd rather be a good reporter than ..

476
00:23:43,705 --> 00:23:44,548
Shakespeare.

477
00:23:45,034 --> 00:23:46,307
Shakespeare was a reporter.

478
00:23:46,423 --> 00:23:47,610
Scooped Queen Elizabeth.

479
00:23:47,925 --> 00:23:49,398
That's the thing to do with dames.

480
00:23:49,637 --> 00:23:51,510
Scoop them but stay away
from orders with them.

481
00:23:52,063 --> 00:23:53,813
Sorry Jonny, but that's
what I want to do.

482
00:23:54,367 --> 00:23:57,183
A man may want to spend ten years
of his life in bed with his hat on.

483
00:23:57,283 --> 00:23:59,002
But he can't. History won't let him.

484
00:23:59,490 --> 00:24:00,467
It will let me.

485
00:24:02,306 --> 00:24:02,978
Maybe.

486
00:24:04,390 --> 00:24:05,271
But I won't.

487
00:24:07,987 --> 00:24:09,059
See you later, pals.

488
00:24:09,722 --> 00:24:12,335
Perhaps we ought to do something
big after we get together again.

489
00:24:12,793 --> 00:24:14,266
Kill the fatted calf or something.

490
00:24:14,472 --> 00:24:15,460
Don't look at me.

491
00:24:15,696 --> 00:24:17,660
I've taken a little weight
but not that much.

492
00:24:18,250 --> 00:24:20,900
We got some presents for you in
our bags as soon as I unpack.

493
00:24:21,095 --> 00:24:23,499
I don't expect much.
Just a diamond bracelet or two.

494
00:24:28,631 --> 00:24:29,818
He's a great kid, Jonny.

495
00:24:30,224 --> 00:24:31,823
Just giving a bum imitation of you.

496
00:24:32,498 --> 00:24:34,915
Can't you see he's got his heart
set on that high-octane upstairs?

497
00:24:35,156 --> 00:24:37,755
And you can't expect a Linotype
machine to win out over that, brother.

498
00:24:38,173 --> 00:24:40,137
May as well sit back and
nature takes its course.

499
00:24:40,237 --> 00:24:43,229
Listen, Evie. I've looked out for
Junior since he wore short pants.

500
00:24:43,825 --> 00:24:45,613
I don't care what he
does with his weekends.

501
00:24:46,048 --> 00:24:48,177
But I do care what he does
with the rest of his life.

502
00:24:48,277 --> 00:24:50,586
But Jonny, you can't ..
- Forget it. Kirk is my problem.

503
00:24:50,802 --> 00:24:52,868
Kirk is Kirk's problem.
Get that through your skull.

504
00:24:53,888 --> 00:24:57,105
Oh sure, sure. But I've always
