you got on your mind.

761
00:37:55,581 --> 00:37:56,310
Alright.

762
00:37:57,452 --> 00:37:58,623
It's Jonny.

763
00:37:59,875 --> 00:38:01,401
It's been Jonny for three years.

764
00:38:01,922 --> 00:38:03,682
Ever since that first time I saw him.

765
00:38:04,257 --> 00:38:05,501
That time he stood you up?

766
00:38:06,485 --> 00:38:07,531
Yeah, I know.

767
00:38:08,332 --> 00:38:10,322
Oh, I've tried to kid myself out of it.

768
00:38:10,593 --> 00:38:12,651
I told myself that it
was all wide-eyed stuff.

769
00:38:13,239 --> 00:38:15,305
Told myself that he was
all bad news. Poison.

770
00:38:15,500 --> 00:38:17,330
That's where I come in? An antidote?

771
00:38:17,549 --> 00:38:19,445
Or did I ever come in at all?
- Oh, Kirk.

772
00:38:20,553 --> 00:38:22,582
I think you're the swell-est
person I've ever known.

773
00:38:23,305 --> 00:38:25,938
And if Jonny hadn't come back.
If he'd only stayed away.

774
00:38:27,657 --> 00:38:28,981
I got to tell you something.

775
00:38:30,182 --> 00:38:31,283
Jonny is a funny egg.

776
00:38:32,370 --> 00:38:33,212
Very funny.

777
00:38:34,854 --> 00:38:36,140
Maybe not his fault.

778
00:38:37,229 --> 00:38:39,160
Women have a habit of
throwing themselves at him.

779
00:38:40,901 --> 00:38:42,567
Alright. I've got that coming too.

780
00:38:43,628 --> 00:38:45,185
I did throw myself at him today.

781
00:38:46,520 --> 00:38:48,421
I suppose I'll always
throw myself at him.

782
00:38:48,776 --> 00:38:50,163
Then just be sure of one thing.

783
00:38:50,682 --> 00:38:52,126
Be sure he is there to catch you.

784
00:38:52,776 --> 00:38:53,705
He'll be there.

785
00:38:54,213 --> 00:38:56,122
Yeah? Wait until the chips are down.

786
00:38:58,138 --> 00:38:59,325
They are down right now.

787
00:38:59,703 --> 00:39:01,268
Stafford wants me to go to Indochina.

788
00:39:02,041 --> 00:39:03,593
Indochina? That's dynamite.

789
00:39:03,834 --> 00:39:06,247
I'm not going, Kirk.
Jonny won't let me leave.

790
00:39:07,665 --> 00:39:08,423
He won't.

791
00:39:08,895 --> 00:39:11,318
You can't care for someone the
way I care for Jonny and have it ..

792
00:39:12,595 --> 00:39:13,660
Well, wasted.

793
00:39:14,177 --> 00:39:15,070
Can't you?

794
00:39:15,369 --> 00:39:17,388
I'm sorry, Kirk.
- Shut up, will you.

795
00:39:18,393 --> 00:39:19,872
Maybe you're right about Jonny.

796
00:39:20,274 --> 00:39:22,104
I don't think so, and I don't hope so.

797
00:39:22,368 --> 00:39:23,475
Please, darling.

798
00:39:24,687 --> 00:39:26,663
I feel like a mule kicked
me right in the stomach.

799
00:39:27,518 --> 00:39:29,201
And I'd like to kill Jonny. That's all.

800
00:39:29,565 --> 00:39:30,666
I'd like to kill him.

801
00:39:31,311 --> 00:39:32,376
Behold us!

802
00:39:33,602 --> 00:39:35,577
Kirk, your dress is wonderful.

803
00:39:36,133 --> 00:39:37,692
Of course, I did just get my hips in.

804
00:39:37,898 --> 00:39:39,956
I think you look pretty demi-mondainey.

805
00:39:40,274 --> 00:39:42,833
If I didn't know you didn't know
French, I'd have to slap you, darling.

806
00:39:43,889 --> 00:39:44,823
Well, kids.

807
00:39:46,025 --> 00:39:47,846
You look elegant. Both of you.

808
00:39:49,499 --> 00:39:53,168
Eve and Willie, will you forgive me?
I don't feel like going out tonight.

809
00:39:54,333 --> 00:39:55,949
As a matter of fact I feel out already.

810
00:39:56,530 --> 00:39:57,361
On my feet.

811
00:40:02,050 --> 00:40:03,323
What's the matter with her?

812
00:40:03,919 --> 00:40:05,392
Whatever it is, it's catching.

813
00:40:06,051 --> 00:40:08,549
All of a sudden I've got a headache.
Let's call off the celebration.

814
00:40:08,649 --> 00:40:09,922
What do you mean, headache?

815
00:40:10,048 --> 00:40:13,271
You just told me you felt like tearing
the town apart with your teeth.

816
00:40:13,691 --> 00:40:15,046
Put in your uppers, Willie.

817
00:40:15,522 --> 00:40:17,023
That's just what we're going to do.

818
00:40:28,846 --> 00:40:30,650
Evie and Willie's was never like this.

819
00:40:34,701 --> 00:40:36,031
Why didn't you unpack for me?

820
00:40:42,777 --> 00:40:44,937
You know, you got the Davis eye, kid.

821
00:40:45,857 --> 00:40:47,566
The girl is terrific.
- What girl?

822
00:40:48,659 --> 00:40:49,545
Your girl.

823
00:40:49,645 --> 00:40:51,640
Sure you don't want to try
and change her status?

824
00:40:51,871 --> 00:40:53,651
It might not be too hard.
- No?

825
00:40:54,228 --> 00:40:54,939
No.

826
00:40:58,491 --> 00:41:00,137
I took her out for a soda.

827
00:41:00,790 --> 00:41:01,744
With bourbon.

828
00:41:02,314 --> 00:41:03,443
We went on from there.

829
00:41:04,004 --> 00:41:05,408
Wound up and Mama Lugovska's.

830
00:41:07,871 --> 00:41:09,692
Wound up how? Tight?

831
00:41:10,098 --> 00:41:11,209
No. Just wound up.

832
00:41:11,810 --> 00:41:13,569
Well, uncoil. What are
you trying to prove?

833
00:41:14,296 --> 00:41:16,827
That it isn't the world that's round,
it is the heels that walk on it.

834
00:41:17,885 --> 00:41:21,294
A guy's a cinch for a new shuffle before
he gets a hand good enough to play.

835
00:41:21,482 --> 00:41:23,630
I expect fast shuffles Jonny,
but not from you.

836
00:41:23,730 --> 00:41:24,631
My deal, kid.

837
00:41:24,731 --> 00:41:27,148
And I didn't get one from Paula either.
- Give her time. You will.

838
00:41:28,196 --> 00:41:30,160
You should know that better than me.
- I should?

839
00:41:30,430 --> 00:41:31,016
Oh.

840
00:41:31,189 --> 00:41:32,519
I saw her after she left you.

841
00:41:33,727 --> 00:41:34,867
A two-timer, huh?

842
00:41:35,186 --> 00:41:36,726
She isn't a woman, she's a football.

843
00:41:36,826 --> 00:41:38,909
What's that, a flag you wave?
Or the double standard?

844
00:41:39,009 --> 00:41:40,825
When a man is a two-timer
that's just normal.

845
00:41:40,925 --> 00:41:42,465
But when a woman is a two-timer ..

846
00:41:42,565 --> 00:41:44,602
She is strong drink and
shouldn't be sold to minors.

847
00:41:44,702 --> 00:41:46,374
I ought to poke you one.
- What for?

848
00:41:47,020 --> 00:41:49,351
If you can't read that babe then
somebody has to do it for you.

849
00:41:50,309 --> 00:41:52,291
You want me to spell out the words?
- Spell away.

850
00:41:52,945 --> 00:41:54,213
It rhymes with "champ".

851
00:41:54,536 --> 00:41:56,276
But it means the opposite.
- I ought to ..

852
00:41:56,376 --> 00:41:57,962
About here.
- About there.

853
00:42:00,101 --> 00:42:02,081
It still rhymes with "champ", kid.

854
00:42:03,442 --> 00:42:05,484
You can't change my mind about Paula.

855
00:42:05,822 --> 00:42:06,494
Champ.

856
00:42:12,104 --> 00:42:12,747
Well.

857
00:42:13,125 --> 00:42:15,581
Well then, maybe we'll have to
fix it so the babe changes hers.

858
00:42:17,345 --> 00:42:19,643
So long, Jonny. It was
nice being related to you.

859
00:42:29,884 --> 00:42:30,727
Hi, Dorloff.

860
00:42:31,138 --> 00:42:32,914
I got a date coming up.
How about the ..?

861
00:42:33,158 --> 00:42:34,580
Oh, it's all yours today, Jonny.

862
00:42:35,303 --> 00:42:36,415
A date, eh?
- Yeah.

863
00:42:36,515 --> 00:42:37,326
A blond?

864
00:42:37,927 --> 00:42:38,971
Everybody is blond.

865
00:42:39,245 --> 00:42:41,493
Tell Mama to ice up a couple
of bottle of champagne.

866
00:42:41,805 --> 00:42:42,826
Champagne?

867
00:42:43,127 --> 00:42:43,799
Jonny.

868
00:42:44,081 --> 00:42:46,521
Well the best is none too
good for everybody's blonds.

869
00:42:46,709 --> 00:42:47,924
Demand isn't good enough.

870
00:42:48,818 --> 00:42:49,824
Jonny.

871
00:42:57,163 --> 00:42:58,750
I suppose I shouldn't have called you.

872
00:42:58,935 --> 00:43:00,678
You just beat me to
the telephone, honey.

873
00:43:01,601 --> 00:43:03,736
You know, all the way over
here I kept telling myself.

874
00:43:04,004 --> 00:43:05,022
Take it easy, Pal.

875
00:43:05,122 --> 00:43:07,423
Just a little more
maidenly modesty please.

876
00:43:09,538 --> 00:43:10,960
The little dining room, baby?

877
00:43:14,961 --> 00:43:16,811
Ah, the heck with maidenly modesty.

878
00:43:17,186 --> 00:43:18,899
Confidence is what a girl needs.

879
00:43:20,137 --> 00:43:21,370
Any place you say, Jonny.

880
00:43:35,374 --> 00:43:37,868
Remind me to be with you the
next time you pick out a hat.

881
00:43:38,506 --> 00:43:40,751
Why, don't you like this one?
- No. There is too much of it.

882
00:43:41,397 --> 00:43:43,322
Hair like that should
be seen not buried.

883
00:43:48,864 --> 00:43:49,650
Come here.

884
00:43:50,546 --> 00:43:51,179
Why?

885
00:43:51,749 --> 00:43:52,818
You need a reason?

886
00:43:53,822 --> 00:43:54,723
It would help.

887
00:43:55,346 --> 00:43:56,833
It's just a step over there but ..

888
00:43:57,584 --> 00:43:58,621
It's a long step.

889
00:43:59,957 --> 00:44:02,013
Where is that confidence
you were talking about?

890
00:44:03,250 --> 00:44:04,754
Alright. I'll give you a reason.

891
00:44:05,848 --> 00:44:07,352
Because it is what you want to do.

892
00:44:08,972 --> 00:44:10,350
It is a long step, Jonny.

893
00:44:10,936 --> 00:44:12,323
Isn't there another reason too?

894
00:44:12,685 --> 00:44:14,740
Alright, alright.
Take your pound of flesh.

895
00:44:16,785 --> 00:44:18,300
It's what I want you to do too.

896
00:44:23,756 --> 00:44:26,614
I don't suppose you'll ever tell a
girl a thing she needs to hear.

897
00:44:27,142 --> 00:44:28,792
There is too much of this coat too.

898
00:44:28,892 --> 00:44:31,003
There is a lot more of you
that shouldn't be buried.

899
00:44:31,103 --> 00:44:32,615
I haven't much time, Jonny.

900
00:44:33,934 --> 00:44:35,264
Have you a stop-watch on you?

901
00:44:36,075 --> 00:44:37,758
I'm supposed to catch a plane at three.

902
00:44:38,013 --> 00:44:39,200
For where, Hoboken?

903
00:44:40,205 --> 00:44:41,764
Stafford has ordered me to Indochina.

904
00:44:42,248 --> 00:44:43,526
Stafford is a mental case.

905
00:44:44,741 --> 00:44:45,670
Indochina, huh?

906
00:44:46,218 --> 00:44:47,373
That's a long way off.

907
00:44:49,326 --> 00:44:50,913
You don't want me to go, do you Jonny?

908
00:44:52,990 --> 00:44:54,274
Well, I do and I don't.

909
00:44:56,389 --> 00:44:58,059
I will take the "do" reasons first.

910
00:44:58,575 --> 00:45:00,534
You are a fire hazard to
some plans that I've got.

911
00:45:02,615 --> 00:45:05,249
A woman doesn't always tie a man down.

912
00:45:06,514 --> 00:45:08,666
Now, why don't you want me to go?

913
00:45:11,988 --> 00:45:13,378
It would be nice to have a row.

914
00:45:15,656 --> 00:45:17,100
Even you can do better than that.

915
00:45:17,804 --> 00:45:19,391
Surely that isn't all you have to say.

916
00:45:21,476 --> 00:45:22,062
No.

917
00:45:22,599 --> 00:45:24,100
I got something else to say, honey.

918
00:45:32,569 --> 00:45:34,172
Goodbye. A pleasant trip.

919
00:45:36,315 --> 00:45:37,044
Goodbye?

920
00:45:39,341 --> 00:45:41,508
That Indochina job is a big opportunity.

921
00:45:42,360 --> 00:45:43,772
I can't ask you to pass it up.

922
00:45:44,995 --> 00:45:47,455
But Jonny, you just said I'd
be nice to have around.

923
00:45:47,984 --> 00:45:49,113
For a couple of weeks.

924
00:45:52,204 --> 00:45:53,276
So that's how it is.

925
00:45:54,108 --> 00:45:55,838
For a couple of weeks?
- That's how it is.

926
00:45:56,203 --> 00:45:59,140
I can say it in six languages but why
make it tough for you to understand?

927
00:46:01,136 --> 00:46:02,909
In what language was that kiss?

928
00:46:03,329 --> 00:46:04,831
The universal language, baby.

929
00:46:05,454 --> 00:46:07,184
And don't tell me you
need an interpreter.

930
00:46:09,336 --> 00:46:10,625
Did I interrupt anything?

931
00:46:11,542 --> 00:46:13,099
Unfortunately, not a thing.

932
00:46:14,458 --> 00:46:15,784
Will you join me, Dorloff?

933
00:46:16,876 --> 00:46:19,017
But the lady?
The champagne was for the lady.

934
00:46:19,284 --> 00:46:20,478
It wasn't needed.

935
00:46:23,406 --> 00:46:24,671
The lady is just leaving.

936
00:46:25,419 --> 00:46:26,663
To the Far East, isn't it?

937
00:46:40,801 --> 00:46:42,140
This I do not understand.

938
00:46:42,723 --> 00:46:44,693
Once, she leaves.
Once, you throw her out.

939
00:46:44,886 --> 00:46:47,169
And obviously you desire to be together.

940
00:46:48,682 --> 00:46:49,875
"Desire" is the word.

941
00:46:51,145 --> 00:46:53,076
Here is something to paste
in your hat my friend.

942
00:46:54,051 --> 00:46:56,722
You can't have your angel cake
and send her to Indochina too.

943
00:47:03,057 --> 00:47:04,734
Where to, Miss?
- China.

944
00:47:43,776 --> 00:47:45,126
Hello Jonny.

945
00:47:45,600 --> 00:47:47,101
Where have you been the last month?

946
00:47:47,290 --> 00:47:48,391
Among the unemployed.

947
00:47:48,792 --> 00:47:50,239
I've also been to Grant's tomb.

948
00:47:50,857 --> 00:47:52,808
The Bronx Zoo and the Aquarium. Twice.

949
00:47:53,237 --> 00:47:55,203
You'd be surprised how
many fish they got there.

950
00:47:55,640 --> 00:47:56,974
Most of them look like Papa.

951
00:47:57,683 --> 00:47:59,462
Oh, go on in and kiss and make up.

952
00:48:00,243 --> 00:48:01,781
I'm glad to see the two of you back.

953
00:48:03,219 --> 00:48:04,048
Two of us?

954
00:48:04,148 --> 00:48:05,694
Sure. Your brother is in there now.

955
00:48:06,052 --> 00:48:07,696
Say, what is wrong between you and Kirk?

956
00:48:07,914 --> 00:48:10,259
When I told him you'd be
here he acted the same way.

957
00:48:10,640 --> 00:48:11,798
Like something bit him.

958
00:48:13,404 --> 00:48:14,276
Where, honey?

959
00:48:18,326 --> 00:48:19,230
Hello Junior.

960
00:48:20,717 --> 00:48:23,375
Oh, you look fine.
Like a collapsed dachshund.

961
00:48:24,255 --> 00:48:25,098
Hello Jonny.

962
00:48:35,520 --> 00:48:38,434
Davis, I've told all this to Kirk. I'll
be brief. He'll give you details later.

963
00:48:39,641 --> 00:48:41,951
As you know The Chronicle
sent Paula Lane to Indochina.

964
00:48:42,255 --> 00:48:43,464
A master-stroke.

965
00:48:43,847 --> 00:48:45,786
She is missing. Disappeared completely.

966
00:48:45,999 --> 00:48:47,746
We've tried every way
we know to find her.

967
00:48:47,846 --> 00:48:49,777
Did you get in touch with
Floyd Kirsten in Hanoi?

968
00:48:49,911 --> 00:48:51,400
Kirsten? That has-been.

969
00:48:51,748 --> 00:48:53,831
He couldn't find his bottle
if it was in his hand.

970
00:48:54,217 --> 00:48:55,453
Okay, I just asked.

971
00:48:56,020 --> 00:48:58,234
Now, I'm worried about Paula.

972
00:48:58,990 --> 00:49:00,892
There just might be a
little trouble with Japan.

973
00:49:01,291 --> 00:49:02,120
Honest?

974
00:49:03,366 --> 00:49:06,371
You'd better rush that tip
over to the State Department.

975
00:49:07,389 --> 00:49:08,690
The long and short of it is.

976
00:49:08,835 --> 00:49:11,497
I want you two boys to go to
Hanoi and find Paula Lane.

977
00:49:14,016 --> 00:49:17,816
It wouldn't be that you want some decent
coverage for The Chronicle, would it?

978
00:49:18,288 --> 00:49:19,704
Let me handle this alone, Chief.

979
00:49:20,213 --> 00:49:21,028
Sorry, boy.

980
00:49:21,225 --> 00:49:22,784
In fairness to The Chronicle I can't.

981
00:49:22,884 --> 00:49:24,271
You couldn't pull it off alone.

982
00:49:24,462 --> 00:49:25,563
With Jonny you might.

983
00:49:25,804 --> 00:49:28,644
He's the kind who gets things done,
no matter who he has to walk on.

984
00:49:29,339 --> 00:49:29,982
Yeah.

985
00:49:30,607 --> 00:49:31,838
You are right about that.

986
00:49:35,621 --> 00:49:37,570
Well, when do you start for Hanoi?

987
00:49:40,265 --> 00:49:41,662
You're sure I'm starting, huh?

988
00:49:42,528 --> 00:49:43,600
That's right, Davis.

989
00:49:44,218 --> 00:49:46,564
I know the spot you're in
because I put you there.

990
00:49:47,120 --> 00:49:48,040
You are broke.

991
00:49:48,140 --> 00:49:50,133
No other paper will touch
you with a ten-foot pole.

992
00:49:50,233 --> 00:49:51,750
I've got you tied up for two years.

993
00:49:52,003 --> 00:49:53,961
And you'd rather be dead
than out of the business.

994
00:49:55,149 --> 00:49:55,829
So.

995
00:49:56,661 --> 00:49:57,962
When do you start for Hanoi?

996
00:50:00,517 --> 00:50:01,675
How's your feet, Chief?

997
00:50:02,695 --> 00:50:03,343
Bad.

998
00:50:03,661 --> 00:50:04,876
I mean your paper's feet.

999
00:50:05,511 --> 00:50:06,484
Cold, as usual?

1000
00:50:07,107 --> 00:50:08,519
You send in your dispatches.

1001
00:50:08,906 --> 00:50:10,407
I'll print them the way I see them.

1002
00:50:10,671 --> 00:50:12,130
I thought so. Very cold.

1003
00:50:13,826 --> 00:50:15,910
You know what cold feet
causes on a newspaper, Chief?

1004
00:50:16,520 --> 00:50:17,518
Poor circulation.

1005
00:50:18,088 --> 00:50:19,481
Or is it the other way around?

1006
00:50:19,966 --> 00:50:22,977
You are not going to bring up my
editorial policy again, are you?

1007
00:50:23,822 --> 00:50:25,872
You don't expect me to keep
it on my stomach, do you?

1008
00:50:25,983 --> 00:50:27,325
Alright, Davis.

1009
00:50:27,739 --> 00:50:28,989
We don't like each other.

1010
00:50:29,288 --> 00:50:31,109
But we work together. Huh?

1011
00:50:33,401 --> 00:50:34,044
Sure.

1012
00:50:34,732 --> 00:50:36,923
Necessity is the mother
of strange bedfellows.

1013
00:50:37,549 --> 00:50:38,364
Eh, Junior?

1014
00:50:39,108 --> 00:50:40,409
Do I put you on the payroll?

1015
00:50:41,652 --> 00:50:42,295
Yeah.

1016
00:50:42,751 --> 00:50:44,469
As of when you took us off.

1017
00:50:46,662 --> 00:50:48,322
It's a deal. How about you, Kirk?

1018
00:50:48,723 --> 00:50:49,515
I'm set.

1019
00:50:49,615 --> 00:50:51,393
Oh sure. Everybody is set.

1020
00:50:52,028 --> 00:50:54,388
Don't you worry, Chief. I'll find
a way to get the news printed.

1021
00:50:54,509 --> 00:50:56,340
How? Taking along a hand-press?

1022
00:50:56,753 --> 00:50:59,785
You'll learn you can't toss me
around like a badminton ball, Davis.

1023
00:51:01,046 --> 00:51:02,969
They don't play badminton
with a ball, Chief.

1024
00:51:03,069 --> 00:51:04,543
They use what is known as a bird.

1025
00:51:04,812 --> 00:51:06,803
You ought to know what that is.
You get it enough.

1026
00:51:29,340 --> 00:51:32,783
More Japanese beetles round here than
you'd see in a California lettuce patch.

1027
00:51:32,883 --> 00:51:35,283
Did we come here worry
about Indochina or find Paula?

1028
00:51:35,777 --> 00:51:38,482
I don't know about you. I'm here
to gather news buds while I may.

1029
00:51:41,041 --> 00:51:44,039
Yes, sir. Than you would find
in a California lettuce patch.

1030
00:51:44,259 --> 00:51:45,732
What kind of a guy are you anyway?

1031
00:51:45,837 --> 00:51:47,710
Paula is a fellow
newspaperman if nothing else.

1032
00:51:48,043 --> 00:51:49,623
For my dough she is nothing else too.

1033
00:51:50,440 --> 00:51:52,971
Are you through trying all the places
that wouldn't know where she is?

1034
00:51:54,298 --> 00:51:55,487
Yeah.
- Okay.

1035
00:51:56,214 --> 00:51:56,972
Hey, cab.

1036
00:51:57,744 --> 00:51:59,388
Now I'll take you to a place that might.

1037
00:52:01,126 --> 00:52:04,021
You see Junior, in every town there is
one guy who knows who's where and why.

1038
00:52:04,248 --> 00:52:06,209
I suppose you mean Floyd Kirsten?
- That's right.

1039
00:52:06,309 --> 00:52:08,648
Stafford told us about him.
He's all washed up and a lush too.

1040
00:52:08,748 --> 00:52:11,403
Maybe, but Kirsten knows more
drunk that Papa does sober.

1041
00:52:18,250 --> 00:52:20,038
Nothing like a little
protective occupation.

1042
00:52:20,354 --> 00:52:21,283
Identification.

1043
00:52:27,710 --> 00:52:28,709
Passports please.

1044
00:52:46,784 --> 00:52:47,566
Excuse.

1045
00:52:48,338 --> 00:52:49,096
Go ahead.

1046
00:52:49,611 --> 00:52:50,369
So sorry.

1047
00:52:51,311 --> 00:52:52,069
So sorry?

1048
00:52:52,212 --> 00:52:54,858
The only thing they're sorry about
is that they can't pull those triggers.

1049
00:52:55,198 --> 00:52:55,956
Yet.

1050
00:52:56,409 --> 00:52:58,797
Come on, buster. Get going before
they ask to see our birthmarks.

1051
00:53:06,399 --> 00:53:07,232
Thank you.

1052
00:53:07,332 --> 00:53:09,727
I hope you're not wasting our time.
- I'm not wasting my time.

1053
00:53:10,751 --> 00:53:13,695
I'll say one thing for Paula. She sure
made this disappearance act look good.

1054
00:53:13,795 --> 00:53:16,298
You think she's pulling a fast one, eh?
- I think she's a smart dame.

1055
00:53:16,606 --> 00:53:19,364
Pretends to get herself in a jam so that
some sap will come tearing after her.

1056
00:53:19,531 --> 00:53:21,174
That's you.
- So why help me find her?

1057
00:53:21,274 --> 00:53:21,975
Simple.

1058
00:53:22,075 --> 00:53:24,831
Sooner you see she's a phony, the sooner
you take other kinds of nourishment.

1059
00:53:27,216 --> 00:53:27,841
Yes?

1060
00:53:27,941 --> 00:53:29,328
We'd like to see Floyd Kirsten.

1061
00:53:30,085 --> 00:53:31,740
We are old friends.
- Friends?

1062
00:53:32,183 --> 00:53:34,342
You are the first of your
race to come for a long time.

1063
00:53:34,624 --> 00:53:35,582
You are welcome.

1064
00:53:36,042 --> 00:53:36,835
Thank you.

1065
00:53:37,901 --> 00:53:38,611
Please.

1066
00:53:48,737 --> 00:53:49,695
Get set, Junior.

1067
00:53:49,939 --> 00:53:51,698
You are about to see
a legend in the flesh.

1068
00:53:51,836 --> 00:53:54,606
A real old-timer. From the
school of Richard Harding Davis.

1069
00:54:02,563 --> 00:54:03,407
Hello Floyd.

1070
00:54:06,895 --> 00:54:08,019
Jonny Davis, Floyd.

1071
00:54:09,504 --> 00:54:11,897
Originator of the Hong Kong
hay ride. Remember?

1072
00:54:13,851 --> 00:54:14,804
Jonny Davis?

1073
00:54:14,904 --> 00:54:16,445
Well, I must say.

1074
00:54:16,545 --> 00:54:17,713
So must I.

1075
00:54:17,957 --> 00:54:19,172
This is my brother, Kirk.

1076
00:54:20,295 --> 00:54:21,596
I'm glad to know you, son.

1077
00:54:21,994 --> 00:54:23,696
It's a privilege to
know you, Mr Kirsten.

1078
00:54:23,853 --> 00:54:24,954
I've read your stuff.

1079
00:54:26,098 --> 00:54:27,355
Not lately, I'm afraid.

1080
00:54:28,548 --> 00:54:31,358
Well, it's been a long time
between by-lines, Jonny.

1081
00:54:32,346 --> 00:54:34,562
My paper has about
given up on me I guess.

1082
00:54:35,163 --> 00:54:36,938
Won't you sit down, gentlemen?
- Thank you.

1083
00:54:37,199 --> 00:54:38,476
Forgive me, Thomas.

1084
00:54:39,016 --> 00:54:40,420
This is Thomas Chang.

1085
00:54:41,322 --> 00:54:42,846
He has been very kind to me.

1086
00:54:43,927 --> 00:54:45,689
He has cared for me here in his house.

1087
00:54:46,229 --> 00:54:47,250
My house is yours.

1088
00:54:47,828 --> 00:54:48,670
Excuse me.

1089
00:54:49,984 --> 00:54:52,589
You see Jonny, I've kinda
lost touch with things.

1090
00:54:54,383 --> 00:54:55,524
I don't write anymore.

1091
00:54:55,743 --> 00:54:58,801
I can see stories but
I can't write them.

1092
00:55:00,189 --> 00:55:01,233
Maybe I'm finished.

1093
00:55:02,337 --> 00:55:05,295
I sort of get buck fever
when I see a typewriter.

1094
00:55:06,572 --> 00:55:07,849
Buck fever, my eye.

1095
00:55:08,029 --> 00:55:10,174
What are you talking about?
You look great, Floyd.

1096
00:55:10,807 --> 00:55:11,799
Thanks, you liar.

1097
00:55:12,782 --> 00:55:15,308
Mr Kirsten, can you help us?
We're trying to find Paula Lane.

1098
00:55:15,876 --> 00:55:17,721
She was sent over here
by The Chronicle and ..

1099
00:55:18,459 --> 00:55:20,614
And we thought since you
know everybody in Hanoi that ..

1100
00:55:25,389 --> 00:55:27,859
The Japs have taken
over here completely.

1101
00:55:29,188 --> 00:55:30,403
They've invaded Thailand.

1102
00:55:31,449 --> 00:55:33,489
Thailand can't resist. Not for long.

1103
00:55:35,278 --> 00:55:38,064
You can't tight tanks with bows and ..

1104
00:55:39,656 --> 00:55:40,447
Arrows.

1105
00:55:40,732 --> 00:55:41,461
Can you?

1106
00:55:42,932 --> 00:55:43,785
Can I help?

1107
00:55:44,103 --> 00:55:44,776
Ming.

1108
00:55:45,170 --> 00:55:47,043
These attacks are common.
- Will he be alright?

1109
00:55:47,265 --> 00:55:48,566
We know how to care for him.

1110
00:55:48,804 --> 00:55:50,197
Take Mr Kirsten to his room.

1111
00:55:50,498 --> 00:55:52,120
Call his doctor.
- Yes, Mr Chang.

1112
00:55:53,408 --> 00:55:55,489
Looks like you're the one
that drew a blank this time.

1113
00:55:55,604 --> 00:55:57,083
Perhaps if you came back later?

1114
00:55:57,346 --> 00:55:58,905
This way, gentlemen.
- No, Mr Chang.

1115
00:55:59,539 --> 00:56:00,305
This way.

1116
00:56:01,138 --> 00:56:04,357
You know, Junior. I think Mr Chang
has something to talk about.

1117
00:56:05,267 --> 00:56:07,438
Now for instance, the Japanese beetles.

1118
00:56:07,993 --> 00:56:10,680
Do you or do you not believe
in pest control, Mr Chang?

1119
00:56:10,877 --> 00:56:11,863
Take either side.

1120
00:56:12,792 --> 00:56:14,367
Which side do you take, Mr Davis?

1121
00:56:14,680 --> 00:56:16,813
I'm for it. I don't like
vermin of any kind.

1122
00:56:19,284 --> 00:56:19,997
Now.

1123
00:56:20,237 --> 00:56:21,338
How about Paula Lane?

1124
00:56:21,904 --> 00:56:24,217
Why do you want to find her?
- We think she's in a jam.

1125
00:56:24,317 --> 00:56:26,442
We're friends of hers.
If that is why you're stalling.

1126
00:56:27,208 --> 00:56:28,520
If you know Mr Kirsten.

1127
00:56:28,905 --> 00:56:30,240
That is probably true.

1128
00:56:30,750 --> 00:56:31,926
Come on. Where is she?

1129
00:56:32,433 --> 00:56:33,849
She has been helping Mr Kirsten.

1130
00:56:34,197 --> 00:56:36,567
She is now at the frontier,
about 200 miles from here.

1131
00:56:36,667 --> 00:56:38,153
The frontier? It's trouble, Jonny.

1132
00:56:38,253 --> 00:56:40,366
It is. And it is very unwise
for me to talk about it.

1133
00:56:40,629 --> 00:56:42,078
It's still more unwise not to.

1134
00:56:42,642 --> 00:56:45,231
If we start crashing up and down
the frontier we'll make a lot of noise.

1135
00:56:45,716 --> 00:56:48,061
You do believe we're on your
side, don't you Mr Chang?

1136
00:56:48,885 --> 00:56:50,289
Yes, I do.

1137
00:56:50,769 --> 00:56:52,229
Otherwise I would send you away.

1138
00:56:52,658 --> 00:56:53,759
Then why the mystery?

1139
00:56:54,370 --> 00:56:55,878
If we find her you will see.

1140
00:56:56,308 --> 00:56:57,437
If we do not find her.

1141
00:56:57,885 --> 00:56:59,749
Then it will do her no
good for you to know.

1142
00:57:00,107 --> 00:57:04,525
So there will be two less people who can
speak in the wrong place about our plan.

1143
00:57:06,194 --> 00:57:07,131
No, Mr Chang.

1144
00:57:07,696 --> 00:57:08,711
Three less people.

1145
00:57:27,867 --> 00:57:29,254
It is three miles to the river.

1146
00:57:29,354 --> 00:57:30,627
On the other side is China.

1147
00:58:39,570 --> 00:58:41,644
We are in luck. They are
going away from the river.

1148
00:58:46,765 --> 00:58:47,943
What about that patrol?

1149
00:58:48,227 --> 00:58:50,043
They won't be back this
way for half an hour.

1150
00:59:00,421 --> 00:59:01,705
What the wigwag?

1151
00:59:02,107 --> 00:59:03,151
I can tell you now.

1152
00:59:03,498 --> 00:59:06,627
They're bringing Chinese children out
of the war zone into French territory.

1153
00:59:07,123 --> 00:59:08,138
There is the boat.

1154
00:59:13,523 --> 00:59:14,939
It looks like they are expected.

1155
00:59:15,070 --> 00:59:16,915
I will go first and tell
them you are friends.

1156
00:59:28,703 --> 00:59:31,492
Isn't it just as dangerous for the kids
over here with all those Japs around?

1157
00:59:32,473 --> 00:59:34,398
Once they are smuggled
in they'll have a chance.

1158
00:59:34,621 --> 00:59:36,180
At least he won't have to duck bombs.

1159
00:59:40,629 --> 00:59:41,358
Come on.

1160
00:59:48,684 --> 00:59:51,379
Shush, children. Quiet.
You must be very quiet.

1161
00:59:52,702 --> 00:59:53,907
That's Paula alright.

1162
00:59:59,780 --> 01:00:00,463
Paula.

1163
01:00:03,932 --> 01:00:05,194
Gee, it's good to see you.

1164
01:00:05,367 --> 01:00:06,783
Are you alright, honey?
- Yeah.

1165
01:00:10,125 --> 01:00:11,941
Oh, you've brought your
big brother too, huh?

1166
01:00:13,617 --> 01:00:14,861
Here, let me take buggins.

1167
01:00:25,476 --> 01:00:27,661
Well, did Stafford send you
over here for silk worms?

1168
01:00:28,157 --> 01:00:30,231
What are you trying to do,
get your name in the paper?

1169
01:00:30,944 --> 01:00:32,394
Here, here. Let me do that.

1170
01:00:33,167 --> 01:00:34,955
Stick around and I'll
give you an interview.

1171
01:00:36,579 --> 01:00:39,395
A nice way to get shot. Smuggling
Chinese kids across the border.

1172
01:00:39,576 --> 01:00:41,888
What is a border?
Just an imaginary line.

1173
01:00:48,508 --> 01:00:49,695
Let us take over, honey.

1174
01:00:49,795 --> 01:00:50,755
Here. Take this.

1175
01:00:53,039 --> 01:00:54,229
Is this the last load?

1176
01:00:54,766 --> 01:00:56,253
Yeah. Yeah we got them all.

1177
01:01:09,387 --> 01:01:10,791
You mislaid a couple.

1178
01:01:19,001 --> 01:01:21,659
All set. Where do they go?
- A little mission down the river.

1179
01:01:21,907 --> 01:01:25,351
Miow will guide them. She's guided many
such groups. There's less risk that way.

1180
01:01:25,887 --> 01:01:26,534
Miow.

1181
01:01:36,654 --> 01:01:38,384
What did you expect to
do with the cannon?

1182
01:01:38,960 --> 01:01:41,280
I expect it to shoot anybody
that tries to stop me.

1183
01:01:41,581 --> 01:01:43,025
You act like these are your kids.

1184
01:01:43,713 --> 01:01:46,941
I think when children are in trouble
they become everybody's kids.

1185
01:01:53,288 --> 01:01:54,639
You could be right, babe.

1186
01:01:58,591 --> 01:01:59,712
Alright, let's go.

1187
01:02:00,431 --> 01:02:02,243
The "sooner I find out
she's a phony", huh?

1188
01:02:08,577 --> 01:02:09,935
Are you sure she will be okay?

1189
01:02:10,112 --> 01:02:12,598
Of course. Very fatigued. Strain.

1190
01:02:12,891 --> 01:02:14,761
But she just lies there.
Doesn't even move.

1191
01:02:15,219 --> 01:02:16,634
I give her a sleeping powder.

1192
01:02:17,558 --> 01:02:19,422
It won't wear off for some time.

1193
01:02:20,419 --> 01:02:22,139
But there is nothing to worry about.

1194
01:02:23,671 --> 01:02:24,572
Who's worried?

1195
01:02:25,146 --> 01:02:25,961
I gather ..

1196
01:02:26,393 --> 01:02:27,122
You are.

1197
01:02:27,684 --> 01:02:28,713
Mister Davis.

1198
01:02:50,497 --> 01:02:53,075
Look, look, look. You've
got your thumb in her eye.

1199
01:02:54,041 --> 01:02:55,512
This isn't man's work anyway.

1200
01:02:55,840 --> 01:02:58,169
Here .. start that story
about Thailand falling ..

1201
01:02:58,357 --> 01:03:00,404
And the Japs will be there
before you get it written.

1202
01:03:22,765 --> 01:03:23,651
Hey, Ming.

1203
01:03:24,995 --> 01:03:25,981
Front and center.

1204
01:03:26,273 --> 01:03:27,548
How is Kirsten?
- Resting.

1205
01:03:27,648 --> 01:03:29,607
That's fine. Look, take
over here honey, will you.

1206
01:03:29,983 --> 01:03:31,845
Give the lady a good
wash and polish job.

1207
01:03:34,781 --> 01:03:36,633
A pretty girl. For a white woman.

1208
01:03:37,608 --> 01:03:39,710
She looks like a piece of
cheese the rats have been at.

1209
01:03:45,325 --> 01:03:46,867
How you coming with the literature?

1210
01:03:46,967 --> 01:03:48,955
The story writes itself.
I'm just feeding it paper.

1211
01:03:49,235 --> 01:03:50,078
A good diet.

1212
01:03:50,669 --> 01:03:51,942
Only if it writes itself ..

1213
01:03:52,042 --> 01:03:54,758
You'd better tell it to write to spell
"perfidy" with an "e" and not a "u".

1214
01:03:55,674 --> 01:03:56,390
Thanks.

1215
01:03:56,597 --> 01:03:58,728
Still great at spelling out
the words for me aren't you.

1216
01:04:02,156 --> 01:04:03,885
Ming, Ming. Gently does it.

1217
01:04:07,045 --> 01:04:08,689
The kid looks like she might break easy.

1218
01:04:09,448 --> 01:04:13,668
When you get that epic finished, you
can tack Floyd Kirsten's name onto it.

1219
01:04:14,791 --> 01:04:16,136
You figure it belongs to him?

1220
01:04:16,236 --> 01:04:18,162
No. I figure it belongs to
anybody who can read.

1221
01:04:20,291 --> 01:04:21,951
No, no. Here, here.

1222
01:04:22,206 --> 01:04:24,865
Let me do it. You're not getting
her ears clean. Get the bed ready.

1223
01:04:46,340 --> 01:04:48,364
I always like women with
their forehead showing.

1224
01:04:49,674 --> 01:04:51,824
Mine never had any to
show about the eyebrows.

1225
01:04:52,139 --> 01:04:53,479
Kirsten's name on this, huh?

1226
01:04:53,667 --> 01:04:54,339
Yeah.

1227
01:04:54,790 --> 01:04:55,834
That's what I said.

1228
01:04:56,870 --> 01:04:57,869
Kirsten's name.

1229
01:04:59,280 --> 01:05:00,409
Send it to his office.

1230
01:05:01,010 --> 01:05:02,368
Not to our office, his office.

1231
01:05:04,081 --> 01:05:05,992
I thought you were
vaccinated against nobility.

1232
01:05:07,611 --> 01:05:09,555
Would you recognise a
needle when you see it?

1233
01:05:10,519 --> 01:05:12,306
I might, if I got the point.

1234
01:05:14,004 --> 01:05:15,305
Stafford will get the point.

1235
01:05:16,069 --> 01:05:17,668
Right in his editorial policy.

1236
01:05:23,927 --> 01:05:25,827
I told him I'd get the news printed.
- Yeah.

1237
01:05:26,202 --> 01:05:28,655
Kirsten gets a by-line and
Stafford gets crossed.

1238
01:05:29,367 --> 01:05:30,688
A beautiful double play.

1239
01:05:31,484 --> 01:05:32,327
Triple play.

1240
01:05:32,904 --> 01:05:34,203
The public gets the truth.

1241
01:05:37,569 --> 01:05:38,727
Not a bad guy, Kirsten.

1242
01:05:39,424 --> 01:05:40,753
He was a good reporter once.

1243
01:05:42,247 --> 01:05:44,187
Which is more than I can
say for you, towhead.

1244
01:05:45,326 --> 01:05:47,085
Some people might want
to vote her a medal.

1245
01:05:47,646 --> 01:05:48,443
What for?

1246
01:05:49,043 --> 01:05:50,201
Running out on her job?

1247
01:05:50,725 --> 01:05:52,950
Playing dry nurse to a
bunch of wet smacks.

1248
01:05:56,849 --> 01:06:00,123
It took a stiff-backed bone at that to
walk up and spit in the Mikado's eye.

1249
01:06:03,383 --> 01:06:04,391
Bed ready now.

1250
01:06:04,757 --> 01:06:05,726
Yep. Alright.

1251
01:06:34,045 --> 01:06:36,231
Okay, honey. I'll call
you when I need you.

1252
01:06:37,567 --> 01:06:39,011
A pretty girl, for a white woman.

1253
01:06:39,234 --> 01:06:40,846
Yeah. You are pretty in any language.

1254
01:06:57,544 --> 01:06:58,931
"Pretty" isn't the word for it.

1255
01:07:00,450 --> 01:07:01,794
What kind of cheese?

1256
01:07:05,237 --> 01:07:07,339
I was wrong about you being
