01:21:55,360 --> 01:21:56,820
Stafford's bloodhounds found you.

1509
01:21:57,501 --> 01:21:59,766
He cabled Kirk he wasn't
sore about that Kirsten story.

1510
01:22:00,565 --> 01:22:01,609
That's nice of him.

1511
01:22:03,002 --> 01:22:03,760
Isn't it.

1512
01:22:04,959 --> 01:22:06,727
He asked Kirk to get
you back on the job.

1513
01:22:07,513 --> 01:22:09,051
He said to leave no stone unturned.

1514
01:22:11,307 --> 01:22:14,593
You can tell Papa you did fine with
all stones until you met Gibraltar.

1515
01:22:15,081 --> 01:22:15,867
That's me.

1516
01:22:16,851 --> 01:22:18,976
That's not why I'm
here in Manila, Jonny.

1517
01:22:19,968 --> 01:22:21,982
I don't care whether you
go back to work of not.

1518
01:22:27,043 --> 01:22:29,403
Honey, what are you trying to do,
work your way through college?

1519
01:22:29,926 --> 01:22:30,655
Kind of.

1520
01:22:31,371 --> 01:22:33,865
I just want to get you back on
your feet for the last round.

1521
01:22:34,564 --> 01:22:35,922
I want you in there, punching.

1522
01:22:37,033 --> 01:22:37,762
At what?

1523
01:22:39,305 --> 01:22:40,423
I don't like set-ups.

1524
01:22:41,128 --> 01:22:43,492
Don't you remember?
We've got a celebration coming to us.

1525
01:22:44,715 --> 01:22:46,770
One we've postponed a couple of times.

1526
01:23:12,351 --> 01:23:14,253
I'm glad to hear you and
Kirk are doing alright.

1527
01:23:15,539 --> 01:23:16,224
Uhuh.

1528
01:23:23,153 --> 01:23:24,235
Yeah, that's fine.

1529
01:23:24,636 --> 01:23:25,913
What recipe did he use?

1530
01:23:26,571 --> 01:23:28,444
Not fair asking a cake how it's made.

1531
01:23:33,921 --> 01:23:35,548
Some cakes should be thoroughly beaten.

1532
01:23:43,200 --> 01:23:44,772
I am so glad.
- For what?

1533
01:23:45,171 --> 01:23:46,120
We stopped.

1534
01:23:46,563 --> 01:23:48,428
It is time to go back
to the hotel isn't it?

1535
01:23:48,528 --> 01:23:50,191
What hotel?
- Your hotel.

1536
01:23:52,124 --> 01:23:53,540
I took a room right next to you.

1537
01:23:54,002 --> 01:23:55,245
Nice of me, huh?

1538
01:23:55,561 --> 01:23:56,847
No. Optimistic.

1539
01:24:01,673 --> 01:24:02,485
Goodnight.

1540
01:24:02,913 --> 01:24:03,737
Goodnight.

1541
01:24:04,194 --> 01:24:04,880
Yes?

1542
01:24:05,941 --> 01:24:07,929
I'm afraid you are the one
who is being optimistic.

1543
01:24:31,398 --> 01:24:32,995
Why don't you try some oil, Jonny?

1544
01:24:33,742 --> 01:24:35,150
Isn't that your speciality?

1545
01:24:36,352 --> 01:24:37,433
What's yours?

1546
01:24:38,314 --> 01:24:39,715
I know a good way to find out.

1547
01:24:41,253 --> 01:24:42,921
We must be thinking of the same one.

1548
01:24:44,636 --> 01:24:45,435
I wonder.

1549
01:24:46,233 --> 01:24:47,875
What I had in mind was you crawling.

1550
01:24:50,308 --> 01:24:51,695
Around the edge of the balcony.

1551
01:24:53,538 --> 01:24:55,813
Well, I was thinking of something
a little less athletic.

1552
01:24:56,219 --> 01:24:57,369
But just as daring.

1553
01:24:58,829 --> 01:25:00,580
Of course, if you are
afraid of falling ..

1554
01:25:02,360 --> 01:25:03,203
Don't worry.

1555
01:25:04,341 --> 01:25:05,975
I always land on my feet.

1556
01:25:07,749 --> 01:25:10,529
The first time I've had my hands on
bamboo since I gave up Mah-jong.

1557
01:25:10,867 --> 01:25:12,317
Really? What make it swell?

1558
01:25:13,402 --> 01:25:14,961
I got splinters under my fingernails.

1559
01:25:15,472 --> 01:25:17,594
You should wear gloves
when you play games.

1560
01:25:17,989 --> 01:25:18,782
I do.

1561
01:25:19,172 --> 01:25:21,274
And I know when to take them off.
And that's right now.

1562
01:25:22,045 --> 01:25:23,346
What goes with you and Kirk?

1563
01:25:24,122 --> 01:25:25,008
Same as ever.

1564
01:25:25,224 --> 01:25:28,129
He's the type of man that signs a
love letter "respectfully yours".

1565
01:25:29,011 --> 01:25:30,992
I didn't know he wrote them.
- He talks them.

1566
01:25:32,197 --> 01:25:33,215
He talks too much.

1567
01:25:34,023 --> 01:25:35,466
He doesn't even know how to kiss.

1568
01:25:36,660 --> 01:25:37,998
I suppose he is learning now?

1569
01:25:38,820 --> 01:25:40,469
Well. He practices enough.

1570
01:25:42,003 --> 01:25:43,333
Let me show you what happens.

1571
01:25:44,111 --> 01:25:45,298
You point at your mouth.

1572
01:25:46,505 --> 01:25:47,863
And then you aim at your ears.

1573
01:25:50,346 --> 01:25:51,962
Of course, it is kind of nice in a way.

1574
01:25:52,280 --> 01:25:53,445
Something like a puppy.

1575
01:25:54,665 --> 01:25:56,166
How would you want him to kiss you?

1576
01:25:57,473 --> 01:25:58,341
Like this.

1577
01:26:01,595 --> 01:26:02,346
Or this.

1578
01:26:04,860 --> 01:26:06,390
So the kid kisses like a puppy, huh?

1579
01:26:06,870 --> 01:26:08,886
Just be patient with him.
He'll be a full-grown dog.

1580
01:26:09,480 --> 01:26:10,609
It runs in the family.

1581
01:26:14,485 --> 01:26:15,623
I thought you would.

1582
01:26:15,855 --> 01:26:17,814
I thought I could make you
cross your own brother.

1583
01:26:17,940 --> 01:26:19,584
He's worth ten of you, a hundred of you.

1584
01:26:19,705 --> 01:26:21,001
How many?
- Two hundred.

1585
01:26:21,902 --> 01:26:24,023
You certainly look very
funny standing there.

1586
01:26:24,259 --> 01:26:25,160
Oh, funny huh?

1587
01:26:25,320 --> 01:26:26,135
Very funny.

1588
01:26:26,570 --> 01:26:27,614
But I can laugh ..

1589
01:26:27,714 --> 01:26:30,728
Because now I'm the one who can turn
around and walk away and not look back.

1590
01:26:31,405 --> 01:26:32,420
So long, Mr Davis.

1591
01:26:32,663 --> 01:26:34,113
Now I don't owe you a thing.

1592
01:27:10,683 --> 01:27:11,496
Paula.

1593
01:27:12,848 --> 01:27:13,634
No lights.

1594
01:27:13,909 --> 01:27:15,913
I don't trust you even with
them on, Jonny Davis.

1595
01:27:19,130 --> 01:27:19,991
Wrong Davis.

1596
01:27:20,632 --> 01:27:21,665
Kirk.
- Yeah.

1597
01:27:21,919 --> 01:27:23,100
And I said no lights.

1598
01:27:23,624 --> 01:27:24,810
I'm giving you a break.

1599
01:27:24,910 --> 01:27:27,123
You probably got cold cream
smeared over your puss anyway.

1600
01:27:27,308 --> 01:27:28,495
I don't get this at all.

1601
01:27:28,596 --> 01:27:30,984
Sorry to barge in. They let me
in Jonny's room. He wasn't in ..

1602
01:27:31,084 --> 01:27:32,997
You expect to find him here?
- Take it easy.

1603
01:27:34,555 --> 01:27:35,341
Hear that?

1604
01:27:35,750 --> 01:27:37,762
Sure. That's just the army.
They always fly around.

1605
01:27:37,862 --> 01:27:39,758
Yeah. Only this time
it is the wrong army.

1606
01:27:40,021 --> 01:27:42,409
Those plans have got the Rising
Sun painted all over their wings.

1607
01:27:43,176 --> 01:27:44,162
Read it and weep.

1608
01:27:44,294 --> 01:27:46,454
I was at The Chronicle office
downtown when this came in.

1609
01:27:46,782 --> 01:27:48,435
Japan just bombed Pearl Harbor.

1610
01:27:55,031 --> 01:27:56,757
[ Air-raid siren ]

1611
01:28:00,804 --> 01:28:02,322
[ Air-raid siren ]

1612
01:28:03,857 --> 01:28:05,829
Any more dope on Hawaii?
- None so far.

1613
01:28:05,929 --> 01:28:06,909
All I know is ..

1614
01:28:07,009 --> 01:28:09,798
Some of those little dickie-birds flew
in at breakfast time and laid some eggs.

1615
01:28:10,402 --> 01:28:12,381
Manila can expect some
of the same any minute.

1616
01:28:12,828 --> 01:28:15,579
Have you cabled The Chronicle?
- No. Censorship slapped on it.

1617
01:28:15,993 --> 01:28:17,726
I don't know how long
it is going to last.

1618
01:28:18,446 --> 01:28:20,953
I guess I won't have to alibi to
Stafford now for not finding Jonny.

1619
01:28:21,944 --> 01:28:23,589
I found him. But not for long.

1620
01:28:23,860 --> 01:28:25,104
Know where he went?
- No.

1621
01:28:25,672 --> 01:28:27,794
At the moment, I didn't care
as long as it was away.

1622
01:28:29,348 --> 01:28:30,563
You're a bad liar, honey.

1623
01:28:31,157 --> 01:28:32,887
You're still stuck on
him as much as ever.

1624
01:28:34,932 --> 01:28:35,596
More.

1625
01:28:36,807 --> 01:28:38,644
But I hate the sight of him too.

1626
01:28:39,286 --> 01:28:40,072
And Jonny?

1627
01:28:40,507 --> 01:28:41,408
How about him?

1628
01:28:42,882 --> 01:28:45,890
Oh, I don't know. Does anybody
ever really know about Jonny?

1629
01:28:46,926 --> 01:28:49,247
I'm for you and you're for
Jonny and he's for himself.

1630
01:28:49,639 --> 01:28:50,997
A nice design for going crazy.

1631
01:28:51,536 --> 01:28:52,784
Yeah, the mystic maze.

1632
01:28:53,066 --> 01:28:54,542
Six ways in and no way out.

1633
01:28:59,787 --> 01:29:00,716
[ Door knocks ]

1634
01:29:07,902 --> 01:29:10,004
Come in out of the night air,
Junior. It's bad for you.

1635
01:29:10,109 --> 01:29:12,120
Hello, Jonny.
- Give me a hand with this, will you.

1636
01:29:13,958 --> 01:29:15,402
You got the wrong room, Mr Davis.

1637
01:29:15,996 --> 01:29:16,931
How was Hanoi?

1638
01:29:17,320 --> 01:29:18,335
Fine. How are you?

1639
01:29:18,512 --> 01:29:19,670
Up to my neck in a war.

1640
01:29:19,770 --> 01:29:21,273
Where's your bags?
- In your room.

1641
01:29:21,373 --> 01:29:23,293
What are you doing?
- Packed?        - Yes.

1642
01:29:23,495 --> 01:29:25,968
Good, Leave them that way. You go
to Australia with towhead here.

1643
01:29:26,368 --> 01:29:27,687
The boat leaves in an hour.

1644
01:29:28,041 --> 01:29:29,431
Listen, if I go to Australia ..

1645
01:29:29,531 --> 01:29:31,994
It will be because I can't stay away
from kangaroos another minute.

1646
01:29:32,529 --> 01:29:34,231
Right now, I can take
them or leave them.

1647
01:29:34,331 --> 01:29:36,465
You'll take them. Here is
what you'll wear on the boat.

1648
01:29:37,779 --> 01:29:40,057
I'm up to my neck in the war
too. I'm not running out on it.

1649
01:29:40,157 --> 01:29:42,210
You're not running out.
The Chronicle is pushing you.

1650
01:29:42,310 --> 01:29:44,285
Here's Stafford's cable.
- Who'll cover Manila?

1651
01:29:44,385 --> 01:29:47,491
I'll cover it like a dirty shirt.
- It took a war to get you back to work?

1652
01:29:47,892 --> 01:29:49,339
This beanie goes with that dress.

1653
01:29:49,939 --> 01:29:52,242
I wouldn't wear these together
if I were going anywhere.

1654
01:29:52,629 --> 01:29:53,651
Which I am not.

1655
01:29:56,939 --> 01:29:58,212
This will go with anything.

1656
01:29:58,366 --> 01:30:00,812
Before we don't leave I'd like to
tell you something about Paula.

1657
01:30:01,016 --> 01:30:02,575
I've heard it. Words and music.

1658
01:30:03,091 --> 01:30:05,204
I need to pack her,
if I do say so myself.

1659
01:30:06,246 --> 01:30:08,520
Listen Jonny Davis, you're not
going to get me out of Manila.

1660
01:30:08,855 --> 01:30:11,217
Not me, it's The Chronicle.
Orders, get it? Orders.

1661
01:30:11,653 --> 01:30:13,476
That goes for you too, Junior.
- I quit.

1662
01:30:13,679 --> 01:30:15,243
Nobody quits. Get your bags.

1663
01:30:16,054 --> 01:30:17,126
Okay, I'll get them.

1664
01:30:17,314 --> 01:30:19,159
You get dressed or I'll
dress you in the taxi.

1665
01:30:22,187 --> 01:30:25,362
Say, who does he think he is?
- He reminds me a little of Jonny Davis.

1666
01:30:25,588 --> 01:30:28,038
Pushing us around. Are you
going to let him get away with it?

1667
01:30:28,409 --> 01:30:29,861
I'm going to let him think he is.

1668
01:30:30,193 --> 01:30:31,351
Never argue with Jonny.

1669
01:30:31,568 --> 01:30:33,642
Just listen to him while
he plays Mister Big.

1670
01:30:33,830 --> 01:30:35,806
And even let him believe
that you agree with him.

1671
01:30:36,060 --> 01:30:36,728
And.

1672
01:30:37,272 --> 01:30:38,545
Figure it out for yourself.

1673
01:30:40,774 --> 01:30:42,418
I think you got something there, Junior.

1674
01:30:50,046 --> 01:30:52,177
Well, how do you think I'll
look in a Red Cross uniform?

1675
01:30:52,613 --> 01:30:54,744
They guys aren't going to
mind getting shot to find out.

1676
01:30:54,894 --> 01:30:56,081
One of them might be me.

1677
01:30:56,763 --> 01:30:58,058
I'm going to join the army.

1678
01:31:01,139 --> 01:31:02,984
I hope Manila is still
there when we get back.

1679
01:31:03,147 --> 01:31:05,049
We'll be standing on that
wharf in half an hour.

1680
01:31:05,447 --> 01:31:07,844
I hope the trip back in the Pilot Boat
won't be too rough on you.

1681
01:31:08,527 --> 01:31:10,586
Not nearly as rough as
fighting it out with Jonny.

1682
01:32:00,661 --> 01:32:01,331
Well.

1683
01:32:01,760 --> 01:32:02,975
Here you are. Sun Valley.

1684
01:32:03,201 --> 01:32:05,478
Thanks Slim. I'll send right
home and get my skis.

1685
01:32:05,896 --> 01:32:08,704
Don't forget to strain the tadpoles out
of that water before you drink it.

1686
01:32:09,023 --> 01:32:10,141
Me drink water?

1687
01:32:10,488 --> 01:32:12,595
That stuff ain't even fit
to wash my feet in.

1688
01:32:23,672 --> 01:32:24,835
Snap into it, Bill.

1689
01:32:27,802 --> 01:32:28,989
Looks like a direct hit.

1690
01:32:29,854 --> 01:32:31,581
Yeah, Right on the ridge.

1691
01:32:32,275 --> 01:32:33,880
Must have aimed at the cross.

1692
01:32:34,377 --> 01:32:35,851
Field Hospital Number 3, huh?

1693
01:32:36,104 --> 01:32:36,811
It was.

1694
01:32:37,776 --> 01:32:39,020
How many got out?
- None.

1695
01:32:39,701 --> 01:32:41,034
Tie that wire off over there.

1696
01:32:41,860 --> 01:32:44,397
A nice little human interest
story for the folks back home.

1697
01:32:44,579 --> 01:32:46,413
Make sure they get it.
What paper you with?

1698
01:32:46,513 --> 01:32:47,605
New York Chronicle.

1699
01:32:47,705 --> 01:32:50,081
I've heard of it. This is that
war it said we couldn't have.

1700
01:32:50,287 --> 01:32:51,880
Oh well, things are different now.

1701
01:32:52,227 --> 01:32:54,860
Pearl Harbor jumped Stafford and The
Chronicle right on the bandwagon.

1702
01:32:55,194 --> 01:32:57,897
Of course I don't know what will happen
when the wagon hits the first bumps.

1703
01:33:00,983 --> 01:33:01,855
All set, sir.

1704
01:33:02,222 --> 01:33:03,808
Then get going, boys. Good luck.

1705
01:33:04,326 --> 01:33:05,484
Got it right here, sir.

1706
01:33:05,865 --> 01:33:06,623
Let's go.

1707
01:33:11,284 --> 01:33:12,042
Where to?

1708
01:33:12,392 --> 01:33:14,469
They'll tell you when they get back.
- From where?

1709
01:33:22,195 --> 01:33:22,858
Hey.

1710
01:33:23,543 --> 01:33:25,584
How about riding with you fellahs?
- No riders.

1711
01:33:25,858 --> 01:33:27,731
Don't tell me you want
us to carry you too?

1712
01:33:28,008 --> 01:33:29,736
Why, on the contrary. Here, allow me.

1713
01:33:30,252 --> 01:33:32,500
You bet. You bet we'll allow you.

1714
01:33:43,343 --> 01:33:45,457
That's dynamite. Don't stub your toe.

1715
01:33:47,612 --> 01:33:49,457
What makes you think
I didn't stub it already?

1716
01:33:57,764 --> 01:33:59,751
The army sure travels on its stomach.

1717
01:34:17,232 --> 01:34:19,392
Good work, Porto.
- Thank you, sir.

1718
01:34:21,326 --> 01:34:22,455
Give him a hand, boys.

1719
01:34:25,095 --> 01:34:26,437
Not a minute too soon.

1720
01:34:32,278 --> 01:34:34,066
My name is Davis, Lieutenant.
Correspondent.

1721
01:34:34,236 --> 01:34:36,086
I hitch-hiked a ride with the boys.
- Oh.

1722
01:34:42,198 --> 01:34:43,607
Quite a landing party.

1723
01:34:44,625 --> 01:34:45,743
A correspondent, eh?

1724
01:34:46,221 --> 01:34:47,064
That's fine.

1725
01:34:47,480 --> 01:34:49,638
We can duck your words.
Can you duck our bullets?

1726
01:34:50,888 --> 01:34:51,775
I can try.

1727
01:34:54,185 --> 01:34:55,013
Davis, huh?

1728
01:34:55,999 --> 01:34:57,670
Ain't one Davis around here enough?

1729
01:35:10,993 --> 01:35:13,324
Dish out the dynamite, Freddy.
Get the men busy on the cookies.

1730
01:35:13,655 --> 01:35:16,253
Yeah, we sure want the right
refreshments for our party.

1731
01:35:16,838 --> 01:35:18,514
We don't want the boys to go hungry.

1732
01:35:27,298 --> 01:35:28,857
You're a dead ringer for my brother.

1733
01:35:29,476 --> 01:35:30,663
Only he is in Australia.

1734
01:35:31,195 --> 01:35:32,256
How do you know?

1735
01:35:33,447 --> 01:35:34,786
I put him on a boat.

1736
01:35:35,002 --> 01:35:36,908
You should have stuck around.
He got off.

1737
01:35:37,668 --> 01:35:39,026
Anybody else get off with him?

1738
01:35:39,481 --> 01:35:41,183
Yeah. An unidentified blond.

1739
01:35:41,819 --> 01:35:43,278
Where is she?
- Back there.

1740
01:35:43,645 --> 01:35:44,460
Back where?

1741
01:35:44,997 --> 01:35:46,394
A place called Sun Valley.

1742
01:35:47,260 --> 01:35:49,114
Oh yeah. I know. I was there.

1743
01:35:50,049 --> 01:35:51,064
What is she doing?

1744
01:35:51,412 --> 01:35:53,356
Probably holding
some lucky stiff's hand.

1745
01:35:53,938 --> 01:35:55,219
She joined the Red Cross.

1746
01:35:56,558 --> 01:35:57,807
Field Hospital Number 3?

1747
01:35:57,990 --> 01:36:00,476
That's right. Field Hospital Number 3.
How come you didn't see her?

1748
01:36:03,647 --> 01:36:04,644
I don't know.

1749
01:36:05,104 --> 01:36:05,947
I guess I ..

1750
01:36:06,719 --> 01:36:07,771
Just missed her.

1751
01:36:08,634 --> 01:36:10,219
You missed me a couple of times too.

1752
01:36:10,764 --> 01:36:13,324
The "forever" set-up. That will get her.
That's what you said.

1753
01:36:15,083 --> 01:36:16,529
Why hold that against me?

1754
01:36:17,008 --> 01:36:19,145
I handed you a golden
blond on a silver platter.

1755
01:36:19,468 --> 01:36:21,482
Don't you know you can't
give people to each other?

1756
01:36:21,582 --> 01:36:23,284
You can't move them
around like checkers.

1757
01:36:23,666 --> 01:36:25,224
I never got within ten yards of her.

1758
01:36:25,324 --> 01:36:26,777
Alright. Let's park it.

1759
01:36:27,741 --> 01:36:29,082
Some things you can't park.

1760
01:36:29,684 --> 01:36:30,899
Take Paula, for instance.

1761
01:36:31,586 --> 01:36:33,937
The thing for you to do is to take
what you can while you can.

1762
01:36:34,037 --> 01:36:35,411
Alright. I said let's park it.

1763
01:36:36,140 --> 01:36:37,306
For the duration.

1764
01:36:38,065 --> 01:36:41,340
Alright, come on, come on.
Help yourselves. Keep them going.

1765
01:36:41,887 --> 01:36:42,873
Keep making them.

1766
01:36:43,211 --> 01:36:44,598
Alright, make with the cookies.

1767
01:36:45,427 --> 01:36:46,816
You too, golden words.

1768
01:36:50,674 --> 01:36:52,060
Ever see these things before?

1769
01:36:52,298 --> 01:36:53,934
Yes, sure. Casey's cookies.

1770
01:36:54,458 --> 01:36:55,969
I gave them a column last week.

1771
01:36:57,049 --> 01:36:58,460
Two parts hollow bamboo.

1772
01:36:58,843 --> 01:37:00,073
One part dynamite.

1773
01:37:00,955 --> 01:37:02,570
Garnished with a percussion cap.

1774
01:37:02,852 --> 01:37:05,465
Drop among buttered Japs
and it mixes them thoroughly.

1775
01:37:05,763 --> 01:37:08,054
The dirty little sons of .. heaven.

1776
01:37:28,363 --> 01:37:29,363
Alright, men.

1777
01:37:41,066 --> 01:37:42,339
We can take our pick, boys.

1778
01:37:42,653 --> 01:37:44,784
We can shoot the enemy out
of the water before he lands.

1779
01:37:44,899 --> 01:37:48,555
Or let him land, try to wipe him out and
capture that beautiful equipment he has.

1780
01:37:48,655 --> 01:37:49,622
Let him land.

1781
01:37:49,722 --> 01:37:51,455
Sure. I hear they carry chocolate bars.

1782
01:37:51,709 --> 01:37:53,093
It is hardly necessary to add.

1783
01:37:53,418 --> 01:37:55,034
We are outnumbered.
- Ain't we always?

1784
01:37:55,249 --> 01:37:56,681
It is getting positively boring.

1785
01:37:56,897 --> 01:37:58,271
We'll make them yell uncle.

1786
01:37:58,371 --> 01:38:01,385
Here is the way I see it.
I want two men, carrying cookies.

1787
01:38:01,803 --> 01:38:05,354
To climb down the cliff and blast the
Japs as they concentrate on the beach.

1788
01:38:06,291 --> 01:38:07,935
They'll make for that canyon down there.

1789
01:38:08,357 --> 01:38:10,254
It is the only way to get
to or from the beach.

1790
01:38:11,098 --> 01:38:12,170
They'll make for it.

1791
01:38:12,347 --> 01:38:13,562
But they won't get there.

1792
01:38:13,759 --> 01:38:16,435
Because the rest of us will be at the
mouth of the canyon waiting for them.

1793
01:38:16,535 --> 01:38:17,855
Who has to toss the cookies?

1794
01:38:17,955 --> 01:38:19,862
Not you Purdy. I've seen you pitch.

1795
01:38:22,025 --> 01:38:23,147
You Porto for one.

1796
01:38:23,419 --> 01:38:24,270
Yes, sir.

1797
01:38:24,688 --> 01:38:25,957
How about me, Lieutenant?

1798
01:38:26,057 --> 01:38:27,900
I used to throw a javelin
for Brooklyn High.

1799
01:38:28,000 --> 01:38:29,156
Alright. You, Davis.

1800
01:38:29,344 --> 01:38:30,102
Yes, sir.

1801
01:38:30,452 --> 01:38:32,268
The rest of you will
follow me to the canyon.

1802
01:38:32,683 --> 01:38:34,442
With the exception
of the visiting fireman.

1803
01:38:34,965 --> 01:38:36,889
And you Purdy, who
will stay in the foxhole.

1804
01:38:37,341 --> 01:38:39,003
Why me? Ain't this a democracy?

1805
01:38:39,322 --> 01:38:39,994
It is.

1806
01:38:40,223 --> 01:38:43,035
You and your machine gun are going to
shield the 2 democrats with the cookies.

1807
01:38:43,268 --> 01:38:45,056
Well, Mama and me
will be in there spitting.

1808
01:39:00,983 --> 01:39:02,043
Fix bayonets.

1809
01:39:07,597 --> 01:39:09,099
Porto. Davis.

1810
01:39:09,653 --> 01:39:11,097
Wait five minutes and then start.

1811
01:39:13,334 --> 01:39:13,977
7:53?

1812
01:39:14,282 --> 01:39:14,986
Right.

1813
01:39:15,916 --> 01:39:18,254
Just in case you boys need
something to get you in the mood.

1814
01:39:18,526 --> 01:39:19,799
Sam brought some news back.

1815
01:39:20,451 --> 01:39:23,123
The Nippos bombed Field
Hospital Number 3 last night.

1816
01:39:23,912 --> 01:39:25,144
All hands lost.

1817
01:39:33,294 --> 01:39:34,411
Come on, democrats.

1818
01:39:35,341 --> 01:39:37,071
And don't forget to
spell our names right.

1819
01:39:39,341 --> 01:39:40,127
Follow me.

1820
01:39:41,697 --> 01:39:43,467
Did you know about Number 3, Jonny?

1821
01:39:43,735 --> 01:39:44,721
Sure. I heard it.

1822
01:39:46,129 --> 01:39:47,430
I let her get off that boat.

1823
01:39:47,876 --> 01:39:49,292
I even put the idea in her head.

1824
01:39:50,298 --> 01:39:51,056
My fault.

1825
01:39:52,678 --> 01:39:54,122
Why didn't you tell me, Jonny?

1826
01:39:56,049 --> 01:39:59,346
I don't put anything in the paper until
I hear it twice and see it three times.

1827
01:40:00,439 --> 01:40:01,606
Here we go, pal.

1828
01:40:03,002 --> 01:40:03,927
Alright, Sam.

1829
01:40:05,655 --> 01:40:07,757
You didn't tell me because
you wanted to give me break.

1830
01:40:09,768 --> 01:40:11,407
I just don't believe it. That's all.

1831
01:40:14,627 --> 01:40:17,015
I can take it, Jonny.
Just like anybody else.

1832
01:40:17,970 --> 01:40:19,872
I guess people can take
a lot when they have to.

1833
01:40:21,689 --> 01:40:22,876
You said something once.

1834
01:40:23,642 --> 01:40:25,118
It makes a lot of sense to me now.

1835
01:40:26,318 --> 01:40:28,691
You said history wouldn't let a
man stay in bed with his hat on.

1836
01:40:30,318 --> 01:40:31,247
You were right.

1837
01:40:31,783 --> 01:40:32,912
See you later, Senior.

1838
01:40:36,042 --> 01:40:38,249
Don't let Mr Moto think
too fast out there, kid.

1839
01:41:12,397 --> 01:41:14,299
Those kids are sure getting
dry behind the ears.

1840
01:41:14,886 --> 01:41:16,718
It must be this tropical sun.
- Yeah.

1841
01:41:23,848 --> 01:41:25,950
You'll get a better look from
down there, golden words.

1842
01:41:27,754 --> 01:41:29,439
Take good care of Mama.
- Uhuh.

1843
01:41:33,943 --> 01:41:35,244
There goes the first cookie.

1844
01:41:41,470 --> 01:41:44,394
The last thing they said to me was
don't forget to spell the names right.

1845
01:41:44,666 --> 01:41:46,912
I got them straight and I want
you to get them straight too.

1846
01:41:47,012 --> 01:41:48,800
Because here is some
of the things they did.

1847
01:41:49,002 --> 01:41:50,004
Take Sam Porto.

1848
01:41:50,361 --> 01:41:51,719
Sam was a dentist from Manila.

1849
01:41:51,957 --> 01:41:53,527
Painless to everybody but the Japs.

1850
01:41:54,909 --> 01:41:57,334
He was a little guy with a great
big grin and a heart to match.

1851
01:41:58,415 --> 01:42:01,681
A party of Nippos were taking cover in
a cave 100 feet below him on the beach.

1852
01:42:02,089 --> 01:42:05,060
The only way Sam could get at them was
to blow the ground from under himself.

1853
01:42:05,626 --> 01:42:08,502
He must have known as he threw that last
dynamite stick that he was going to die.

1854
01:42:08,742 --> 01:42:10,072
But he threw it all the same.

1855
01:42:14,127 --> 01:42:16,079
That was Sam Porto and
don't forget the name.

1856
01:42:19,011 --> 01:42:20,918
Take Kirk Davis, ex-war correspondent.

1857
01:42:21,106 --> 01:42:24,621
He was halfway down a cliff stood on a
ledge not wide enough for his number 9s.

1858
01:42:25,170 --> 01:42:27,595
He made a target that would
gladden the heart of a Jap gunner ..

1859
01:42:27,695 --> 01:42:30,501
But he was in a position to do plenty
of damage if they didn't see him first.

1860
01:42:30,704 --> 01:42:32,702
The Japs were setting up
house in another cave ..

1861
01:42:32,802 --> 01:42:34,947
Where they could rake the
beach with machine gun fire.

1862
01:42:38,400 --> 01:42:40,566
Lieutenant Halls led his
men out of the canyon.

1863
01:42:41,013 --> 01:42:42,176
Don't forget the name.

1864
01:42:42,357 --> 01:42:44,545
Lieutenant Wade Halls West Point 1937.

1865
01:42:45,346 --> 01:42:49,179
By now the Japs had got the ticker going
and a Filipino scout, Manuel Ortega ..

1866
01:42:49,604 --> 01:42:52,052
Don't forget that name,
copped a full burst.

1867
01:42:58,934 --> 01:43:00,661
Soldier Davis couldn't reach that gun.

1868
01:43:00,947 --> 01:43:03,123
But he could reach that big
rock balanced above it.

1869
01:43:11,325 --> 01:43:13,225
He did Brooklyn High
proud with that throw.

1870
01:43:13,442 --> 01:43:15,722
As a javelin thrower he stepped
right into the limelight.

1871
01:43:16,086 --> 01:43:18,607
But the limelight doesn't pay off
when the other guy has got a gun.

1872
01:43:19,703 --> 01:43:21,295
A Jap plane came out of nowhere.

1873
01:43:25,756 --> 01:43:29,110
And turned soldier Davis into a gold
star on his High School service flag.

1874
01:43:29,911 --> 01:43:32,027
That was Kirk Davis.
Don't forget the name.

1875
01:43:32,748 --> 01:43:36,531
Don't forget Sergeant Tom Purdy who used
to bend a gas hose in Butte Montana.

1876
01:43:37,539 --> 01:43:41,363
That same Jap plane dived on the foxhole
and shot the legs out from under Mama.

1877
01:43:47,224 --> 01:43:49,068
"Mama" was what he
called his machine gun.

1878
01:43:49,267 --> 01:43:52,511
I almost feel the Montana democrat would
rather have stopped the bullets himself.

1879
01:43:53,052 --> 01:43:54,821
He was as sore as a boiled owl.

1880
01:43:57,307 --> 01:43:59,687
Lieutenant Halls was coming on
again but so was the Jap plane.

1881
01:44:01,701 --> 01:44:04,403
Halls got one through the leg
and he hit the sand face down.

1882
01:44:05,406 --> 01:44:08,290
Sergeant Purdy picked up his busted Mama
and mounted it against his own body.

1883
01:44:08,478 --> 01:44:10,487
Kicking like forty mules straight away.

1884
01:44:19,737 --> 01:44:22,707
That Jap flyer went hunting his
ancestors in the Bataan jungle.

1885
01:44:22,988 --> 01:44:24,804
But there wasn't much
left of Sergeant Purdy.

1886
01:44:25,219 --> 01:44:27,998
He only lived long enough to know
that he and Mama had done their job.

1887
01:44:28,585 --> 01:44:31,101
Sergeant Tom Purdy.
Don't forget the name.

1888
01:44:32,610 --> 01:44:35,924
Halls still had one good leg and a
dozen hard guys alongside him.

1889
01:44:36,242 --> 01:44:37,629
He couldn't walk. He could hop.

1890
01:44:37,737 --> 01:44:39,296
But he couldn't talk. He could point.

1891
01:44:41,589 --> 01:44:44,127
Thanks to Porto and Davis
the Japs were out in the open.

1892
01:44:46,267 --> 01:44:49,984
Thanks to Tom Purdy, all they had to
worry about now was being outnumbered.

1893
01:44:58,605 --> 01:45:00,834
Those hard guys charged and
that little scuffle was over.

1894
01:45:01,218 --> 01:45:03,137
Not so fast, Mr Davis.
- I'm sorry, kid.

1895
01:45:15,439 --> 01:45:17,289
The little scuffle was
over and it was won.

1896
01:45:17,389 --> 01:45:19,434
And it wasn't just a win.
It proved something bigger.

1897
01:45:21,661 --> 01:45:23,396
I'll catch up with
you later, Lieutenant.

1898
01:45:29,689 --> 01:45:31,868
Brown men and white men
fought and died together.

1899
01:45:32,381 --> 01:45:34,369
When they bled, their
blood was the same color.

1900
01:45:34,469 --> 01:45:35,742
And don't forget the names.

1901
01:45:38,186 --> 01:45:40,332
Lieutenant Wade Halls,
Sergeant Tom Purdy.

1902
01:45:41,451 --> 01:45:44,267
Privates Manuel Ortega,
Sam Porto and Kirk Davis.

1903
01:45:44,740 --> 01:45:45,869
They lost their lives.

1904
01:45:46,851 --> 01:45:49,163
No that's wrong. They didn't
lose them, they gave them up.

1905
01:45:49,404 --> 01:45:50,995
And I ask you not to forget the names.

1906
01:45:51,777 --> 01:45:52,553
Jonny.

1907
01:46:01,329 --> 01:46:02,784
I heard you just now, Jonny.

1908
01:46:03,225 --> 01:46:03,884
Kirk?

1909
01:46:03,984 --> 01:46:06,700
Stop snivelling, towhead.
You don't cry for heroes.

1910
01:46:11,539 --> 01:46:13,360
Say, where do you keep
your rabbit's foot?

1911
01:46:13,460 --> 01:46:15,531
I heard everybody in
Hospital Number 3 got it.

1912
01:46:17,395 --> 01:46:18,496
On one of the breaks.

1913
01:46:19,062 --> 01:46:20,420
I was coming back with some ..

1914
01:46:20,663 --> 01:46:21,821
Food and clothes and ..

1915
01:46:22,888 --> 01:46:24,802
Is this all, Mr Davis?
Shall I mark it ready?

1916
01:46:24,902 --> 01:46:27,564
No. More to come. But you'd better
get moving with what you've got.

1917
01:46:27,664 --> 01:46:29,480
The radio can't last much longer.
- Yes, sir.

1918
01:46:29,939 --> 01:46:31,984
Put in a fresh sheet, honey.
We'll write it together.

1919
01:46:38,069 --> 01:46:39,799
We won that little fight
with the cookies.

1920
01:46:40,284 --> 01:46:43,206
Now, we won't be winning any more that
you hear about on the Bataan peninsula.

1921
01:46:44,238 --> 01:46:45,282
The big push is on.

1922
01:46:46,070 --> 01:46:48,373
They're throwing the book at us.
0rders have come to evacuate.

1923
01:46:48,545 --> 01:46:50,247
Tomorrow morning the
headlines will read:

1924
01:46:50,362 --> 01:46:52,297
"<i>BATAAN FALLS!</i>"

1925
01:46:53,287 --> 01:46:54,827
The headlines will be wrong though.

1926
01:46:54,927 --> 01:46:58,171
Because Bataan has not fallen. It has
stood for 94 days and it still stands.

1927
01:47:00,067 --> 01:47:02,856
The best delaying action of the war was
fought in an area the size of a county.

1928
01:47:03,339 --> 01:47:05,817
300,000 Japanese were
tied in knots long enough.

1929
01:47:05,917 --> 01:47:08,077
For the USA to get its Sunday
clothes off and go to work.

1930
01:47:08,431 --> 01:47:09,444
Hold it, Jonny.

1931
01:47:12,248 --> 01:47:12,937
Okay.

1932
01:47:13,037 --> 01:47:15,192
If a handful of Americans
and Filipinos can do all that.

1933
01:47:16,275 --> 01:47:19,676
Living off rice and mule-meat,
fighting with bricks, bats and bolas.

1934
01:47:19,999 --> 01:47:21,557
Then Bataan still stands.

1935
01:47:22,938 --> 01:47:25,656
The battle of Bataan was lost. By Japan.

1936
01:47:27,415 --> 01:47:29,187
In case the Japanese
don't realize that ..

1937
01:47:29,287 --> 01:47:31,830
I've a message for them from the
men dead and living, of Bataan.

1938
01:47:32,476 --> 01:47:33,395
More to come.

1939
01:47:34,362 --> 01:47:36,850
That is a newspaper term and it
means the story isn't finished.

1940
01:47:37,300 --> 01:47:39,163
And the punch line has
not been written yet.

1941
01:47:40,099 --> 01:47:41,479
Remember that, Tokyo.

1942
01:47:41,931 --> 01:47:42,995
More to come.

1943
